# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dnxhr-codec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] , with the color of each resolution type indicating the display ratio (e.g. red indicates a 4:3 ratio).
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] In the cinematography industry, 2K resolution traditionally refers to a digital scan of 35 mm film with a resolution around 2000 pixels wide.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] Typically this is done at 2048 × 1556, but the exact dimensions vary based on the aspect ratio and size of the scan area.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] In modern cinema, another common 2K resolution is 2048 × 1080.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] This is the resolution of the 2K container format standardized by DCI in their Digital Cinema System Specification in 2005.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] However, the term *2K* itself is generic, was not coined by DCI, and does not refer specifically to the DCI 2K standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] Usage of the term *2K* predates the publication of the DCI standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] The resolution 1920 × 1080 has also been referred to as a 2K resolution by other standards organizations like NHK Science & Technology Research Laboratories and ITU Radiocommunication Sector (which were involved in the standardization of 1080p HDTV and 4K UHDTV).
[src:dnxhr-codec/2k-resolution] In consumer products, 2560 × 1440 (1440p) is sometimes referred to as *2K*, but it and similar formats are more traditionally categorized as 2.5K resolutions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The 4K television market share increased as prices fell dramatically throughout 2013 and 2014.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The term **4K** is generic and refers to any resolution with a horizontal pixel count of approximately 4,000.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Several different 4K resolutions have been standardized by various organizations.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 4K resolution is approximately 8 million pixels, which is 4 times as many as 1080p.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2005, Digital Cinema Initiatives (DCI), a prominent standards organization in the cinema industry, published the **Digital Cinema System Specification**.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This specification establishes standardized 2K and 4K container formats for digital cinema production, with resolutions of 2048 × 1080 and 4096 × 2160 respectively.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 2K distributions can have a frame rate of either 24 or 48 FPS, while 4K distributions must have a frame rate of 24 FPS.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Some articles claim that the terms **2K** and **4K** were coined by DCI and refer exclusively to the 2K and 4K formats defined in the DCI standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] However, usage of these terms in the cinema industry predates the publication of the DCI standard, and they are generally understood as casual terms for any resolution approximately 2000 or 4000 pixels in width, rather than names for specific standard resolutions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2007, the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers published *SMPTE ST 2036-1*, which defines parameters for two UHDTV systems called **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2**.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2012, the International Telecommunication Union, Radiocommunication Sector published Recommendation BT.2020, also known as the Ultra High Definition Television (UHDTV) standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] It adopts the same image parameters defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Although the UHDTV standard does not define any official names for the formats it defines, ITU typically uses the terms **4K**, **4K UHD**, or **4K UHDTV** to refer to the 3840 × 2160 system in public announcements and press releases (**8K** for the 7680 × 4320 system).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In some of ITU's other standards documents, the terms **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2** are used as shorthand.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In October 2012, the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) announced its definition of the term **Ultra High-Definition** (or **Ultra HD**) for use with marketing consumer display devices.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The CEA definition does allow manufacturers to use other terms—such as **4K**—alongside the Ultra HD logo.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Since the resolution in CEA's definition is only a minimum requirement, displays with higher resolutions such as 4096 × 2160 or 5120 × 2880 also qualify as "Ultra HD" displays, provided they meet the other requirements.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Some 4K resolutions, like 3840 × 2160, are often casually referred to as **2160p**.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The term **2160p** could be applied to any format with a height of 2160 pixels, but it is most commonly used in reference to the 4K UHDTV resolution of 3840 × 2160 due to its association with the well-known 720p and 1080p HDTV formats.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Although 3840 × 2160 is both a 4K resolution and a 2160p resolution, these terms cannot always be used interchangeably since not all 4K resolutions are 2160 pixels tall, and not all 2160p resolutions are ≈4000 pixels wide.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] However, some companies have begun using the term "4K" to describe devices with support for a 2160p resolution, even if it is not close to 4000 pixels wide.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] For example, many "4K" dash cams only support a resolution of 2880 × 2160 (4∶3); although this is a 2160p resolution, it is not a 4K resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Conversely, Samsung released a 5120 × 2160 (64∶27) TV, but marketed it as a "4K" TV despite its 5K-class resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2015, LG Display announced the implementation of a new technology called M+, which is the addition of white subpixels along with the regular RGB dots in their IPS panel technology.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The media and internet users later called this "RGBW" TVs because of the white sub pixel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Most of the new M+ technology was employed on 4K TV sets, which led to a controversy after tests showed that the addition of a white subpixel replacing the traditional RGB structure would reduce the resolution by around 25%.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] After tests done by Intertek in which the technical aspects of LG M+ TVs were analyzed and they concluded that "the addressable resolution display is 2,880 X 2,160 for each red, green, blue", in other words, the LG TVs were technically 2.8K as it became known in the controversy.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This negatively impacts the rendering of text, making it a bit fuzzier, which is especially noticeable when a TV is used as a PC monitor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2019, Sony was granted the CinemaWide trademark by the European Union Intellectual Property Office (EUIPO), in which the trademark covers 'Class 9' electronic devices, including smartphones.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Sony Xperia smartphones are the most widely known products that equipped with CinemaWide 4K display, such as Xperia 1, Xperia 1 II, Xperia 1 III, Xperia 1 IV and Xperia 1 V.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Video sharing website YouTube and the television industry have adopted 3840 × 2160 as their 4K standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] As of 2014, 4K content from major broadcasters remained limited.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] By late 2014, 4K content was becoming more widely available online, including on Apple TV, YouTube, Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] By 2013, some UHDTV models were available to general consumers in the range of US$600.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] As of 2015, prices on smaller computer and television panels had dropped below US$400.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On March 26, 2013, the Advanced Television Systems Committee announced new proposals of a new standard called ATSC 3.0 which would implement UHD broadcasts at resolutions of up to 3840 × 2160 or 7680 × 4320.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The standard would also include framerates of up to 120 Hz, HEVC encoding, wide color gamut, as well as high dynamic range.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2014, the Digital Video Broadcasting Project released a new set of standards intended to guide the implementation of high-resolution content in broadcast television.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Dubbed **DVB-UHDTV**, it establishes two standards, known as **UHD-1** (for 4K content) and **UHD-2** (for 8K content).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] These standards use resolutions of 3840 × 2160 and 7680 × 4320 respectively, with framerates of up to 60 Hz, color depth up to 10 bpc (30 bit/px), and HEVC encoding for transmission.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] DVB is currently focusing on the implementation of the UHD-1 standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] DVB finalized **UHD-1 Phase 2** in 2016, with the introduction of service by broadcasters expected in 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] UHD-1 Phase 2 adds features such as high dynamic range (using HLG and PQ at 10 or 12 bits), wide color gamut (BT.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] As of February 2025, both YouTube and Vimeo support high-resolution video uploads, with maximum resolutions of 4096 × 2304 pixels (approximately 9.4 megapixels) and 4096 × 2160 pixels (approximately 8.8 megapixels), respectively.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The growing availability of 4K content across streaming platforms like Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, and YouTube has made it more accessible to consumers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Vimeo's 4K content is currently limited to mostly nature documentaries and tech coverage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) facilitates streaming of 4K content at bitrates between 20 and 30 Mbit/s, offering efficient compression without significant quality loss.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In January 2014, Naughty America launched the first adult video service streaming in 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In February 2025, Super Bowl LIX was broadcast in 4K resolution with Dolby Vision HDR and Dolby Atmos sound for the first time.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Fox aired the game, and it was also available for free streaming in 4K on Tubi, marking a significant milestone in sports broadcasting.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The first mobile phones to be able to record at 2160p (3840 × 2160) were released in late 2013, including the Samsung Galaxy Note 3, which is able to record 2160p at 30 frames per second.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In the year 2014, the OnePlus One was released with the option to record DCI 4K (4096 × 2160) at 24 frames per second, as well as LG G3 and Samsung Galaxy Note 4 with optical image stabilization.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In the year 2015, Apple announced the iPhone 6s was released with the 12 megapixel camera that has the option to record 4K at 25 or 30 frames per second.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In the years 2017 and 2018, mobile phone chipsets reached sufficient processing power that mobile phone vendors started releasing mobile phones that allow recording 2160p footage at 60 frames per second for a smoother and more realistic appearance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] iMac with Retina Display (2014) is one of the earliest computers that utilise 4K widescreen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 1981, the NEC μPD7220 computer graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×1024p (progressive scan) or 4096×2048i (interlaced).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 1984, Hitachi's ARTC HD63484 graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×2048p (progressive scan) or 4096×4096i (interlaced), targeted at the bit-mapped desktop publishing market.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2000, JVC introduced the first 4K digital cinema video projector using D-ILA technology.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The first commercially available 4K camera for cinematographic purposes was the Dalsa Origin, released in 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Sony began offering 4K digital cinema projectors in 2004.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 4K digital projectors were introduced to movie theaters in 2005, but most theaters continued using analog movie projectors until 4K digital projectors eventually replaced them by 2011.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 4K streaming technology was developed during the mid-to-late 2000s by several research groups in universities around the world, such as University of California, San Diego, CALIT2, Keio University and Naval Postgraduate School.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] They realized several demonstrations in venues such as IGrid in 2004 and CineGrid.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] YouTube began supporting 4K for video uploads in 2010 as a result of leading manufacturers producing 4K cameras.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Users could view 4K video by selecting "Original" from the quality settings until December 2013, when the 2160p option appeared in the quality menu.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In November 2013, YouTube began to use the VP9 video compression standard, saying that it was more suitable for 4K than High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Google, which owns YouTube, developed VP9.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The first 4K home theater projector was released by Sony in 2012.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Despite this, as of 2023, there are not many finished films with 4K resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Even for movies and TV shows shot using 6K or 8K cameras, almost all finished films are edited in HD resolution and enlarged to fit a 4K format.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Sony is one of the leading studios promoting UHDTV content, as of 2013 offering a little over 70 movie and television titles via digital download to a specialized player that stores and decodes the video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The large files (≈40 GB), distributed through consumer broadband connections, raise concerns about data caps.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2014, Netflix began streaming *House of Cards*, *Breaking Bad*, and "some nature documentaries" at 4K to compatible televisions with an HEVC decoder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Most 4K televisions sold in 2013 did not natively support HEVC, with most major manufacturers announcing support in 2014.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Amazon Studios began shooting their full-length original series and new pilots with 4K resolution in 2014.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] They are now currently available through Amazon Video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In March 2016 the first players and discs for Ultra HD Blu-ray—a physical optical disc format supporting 4K resolution and high-dynamic-range video (HDR) at 60 frames per second—were released.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On August 2, 2016, Microsoft released the Xbox One S, which supports 4K streaming and has an Ultra HD Blu-ray disc drive, but does not support 4K gaming.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On November 10, 2016, Sony released the PlayStation 4 Pro, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though many games use checkerboard rendering or are upscaled 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On November 7, 2017, Microsoft released the Xbox One X, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though not all games are rendered at native 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Though the price of home cinema viewing devices began to drop rapidly from 2013, the digital video projector market saw limited expansion as very few manufacturers had fully 4K-capable lineups.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Native 4K projectors remained priced in the five-figure range well into 2015, only falling below US$10,000 later that year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Sony was the sole major manufacturer offering a comprehensive 4K projection solution as of 2015.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Critics argue that, at typical direct-view panel sizes and viewing distances, the extra pixels of 4K are unnecessary for normal human vision.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In contrast, home cinema projectors use larger screens without necessarily increasing the viewing distance to match the scale.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This technology reached its fourth generation in 2016.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] JVC applied this technology to create an 8K flight simulation system for Boeing, meeting the visual acuity limits of 20/25.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The first pixel-shifted 4K UHD projectors adopted by the market are Optoma, BenQ, Dell, et al., for those adopt a 2718×1528 pixel structure.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The amount of data these projectors process is true 4K, but they overlap the pixels, which is what pixel shifting is.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In fact, each of those pixels is far larger.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In fact, each one has 50% more area than true 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This way, they project a pixel and shift it up to the right by a half diameter and project it again with modified data—the second pixel overlaid on the first.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This would result in adjacent red and green pixels effectively forming yellow, with a fringe on one side of red, on the other of green—except that the fringe takes on another color as the next line of pixels overlaps too.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 4K UHD or 1080p pixel shifting cannot reveal the fine detail of a true 4K projector such as those Sony ships in the business, education, and home markets.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] While projecting UHD, it might look as though the pixel structures would have 1/4 the area of 1080p; it just doesn't happen with pixel shifting.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] That much resolution is only carried by a true 4K projector.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This is why "true" 4K costs so much more than 4K UHD projectors that have more or less similar feature sets.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] They produce smaller pixels, finer resolution—no loss of detail or color from the overlapping pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This is in stark contrast to the small variation in the aspect ratio difference, which would be capable of being noticeable in a few companies, such as Kaleidescape, offering media servers that enable 4K UHD Blu-ray movies with a wide dynamic range in a home theater.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In November 2014, American satellite provider DirecTV (owned by AT&T) became the first pay-TV provider to offer access to 4K content, although limited to selected video-on-demand films.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In August 2015, British sports network BT Sport launched a 4K feed, with its first broadcast being the 2015 FA Community Shield football match.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Two production units were used, producing the traditional broadcast in high-definition, and a separate 4K broadcast.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] As the network did not want to mix 4K footage with upconverted HD footage, this telecast did not feature traditional studio segments at pre-game or half-time, but those hosted from the stadium by the match commentators using a 4K camera.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] BT envisioned that if viewers wanted to watch studio analysis, they would switch to the HD broadcast and then back for the game.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Footage was compressed using H.264 encoders and transmitted to BT Tower, where it was then transmitted back to BT Sport studios and decompressed for distribution, via 4K-compatible BT TV set-top boxes on an eligible BT Infinity internet plan with at least a 25 Mbit/s connection.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In late 2015 and January 2016, three of Canada's television providers – including Quebec-based Vidéotron, Ontario-based Rogers Cable, and Bell Fibe TV, announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes that can stream 4K content to subscribers over gigabit internet service.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Bell Media announced via its TSN division a slate of 4K telecasts to begin on January 20, 2016, including selected Toronto Raptors games and regional NHL games.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On January 14, 2016, in cooperation with BT Sport, Sportsnet broadcast the first ever NBA game produced in 4K – a Toronto Raptors/Orlando Magic game at O2 Arena in London, England.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] On January 20, also during a Raptors game, TSN presented the first live 4K telecast produced in North America.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Three days later, Sportsnet presented the first NHL game in 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] For the opening game of the 2016 Toronto Blue Jays season, Dome constructed "Trillium" – a production truck integrating both 4K and 1080i high-definition units.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Bell Media's CTV also broadcast the 2016 Juno Awards in 4K as the first awards show presented in the format.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In February 2016, Spanish-language Univision trialed 4K by producing a closed-circuit TV broadcast of a football friendly between the national teams of Mexico and Senegal from Miami (America) in the format.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The broadcast was streamed privately to several special viewing locations.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Univision aimed to develop a 4K streaming app to publicly televise the final of Copa América Centenario in 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In March 2016, DirecTV and CBS Sports announced that they would produce the "Amen Corner" supplemental coverage from the Masters golf tournament in 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In late 2016, Telus TV announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] After having trialed the technology in limited matches at the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup, and the 2014 FIFA World Cup (via private tests and public viewings in the host city of Rio de Janeiro), the 2018 FIFA World Cup was the first FIFA World Cup in which all matches were produced in 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Host Broadcasting Services stated that at least 75% of the broadcast cut on each match would come from 4K cameras (covering the majority of main angles), with instant replays and some camera angles being upconverted from 1080p sources.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] These broadcasts were made available from selected rightsholders, such as the BBC in the UK, and selected television providers in the United States.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Technical limitations in distributing 4K broadcasts (including the increased cost of 4K-compatible production equipment) have led to some broadcasters deciding against the format in favour of emphasizing 1080p/HDR broadcasts instead.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] After having broadcast UEFA Euro and the Champions League final in the format, UEFA discontinued 4K coverage for both in 2024, as broadcasters elected to put resources behind HDR and other on-air features instead.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Some U.S. broadcasters, such as CBS Sports, Fox Sports, and USA Network have broadcast events promoted as having "4K" feeds, but are actually 1080p/HDR broadcasts upconverted to 4K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] For the 2024 Summer Olympics, USA Network's "4K" coverage was sourced from host broadcaster Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS) in 4K, but downconverted to 1080p when received by NBC Sports' studios, and then upconverted to 4K for distribution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 is the dominant 4K resolution in the consumer media and display industries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This is the resolution of the UHDTV1 format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the 4K UHDTV format defined by ITU-R in Rec.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] 2020, and is also the minimum resolution for CEA's definition of **Ultra HD** displays and projectors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 was also chosen by the DVB project for their 4K broadcasting standard, UHD-1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This resolution has an aspect ratio of 16∶9, with 8,294,400 total pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] It is exactly double the horizontal and vertical resolution of 1080p (1920 × 1080) for a total of 4 times as many pixels, and triple the horizontal and vertical resolution of 720p (1280 × 720) for a total of 9 times as many pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] It is sometimes referred to as "2160p", based on the naming patterns established by the previous 720p and 1080p HDTV standards.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In 2013, televisions capable of displaying UHD resolutions were seen by consumer electronics companies as the next trigger for an upgrade cycle after a lack of consumer interest in 3D television.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This resolution is used mainly in digital cinema production, and has a total of 8,847,360 pixels with an aspect ratio of 256∶135 (≈19∶10).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] It was standardized as the resolution of the 4K container format defined by Digital Cinema Initiatives in the Digital Cinema System specification, and is the native resolution of all DCI-compliant 4K digital projectors and monitors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The DCI specification allows several different resolutions for the content inside the container, depending on the desired aspect ratio.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The DCI 4K standard has twice the horizontal and vertical resolution of DCI 2K (2048 × 1080), with four times as many pixels overall.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Digital movies made in 4K may be produced, scanned, or stored in a number of other resolutions depending on what storage aspect ratio is used.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] In the digital cinema production chain, a resolution of 4096 × 3112 is often used for acquiring "open gate" or anamorphic input material, a resolution based on the historical resolution of scanned Super 35 mm film.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] The main advantage of recording video at the 4K standard is that fine spatial detail is resolved well.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Individual still frames extracted from 3840×2160-pixel video footage can act as 8.3 megapixel still photographs, while only 2.1 megapixels at 1080p and 0.9 megapixels at 720p.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] If the final video resolution is reduced to 2K from a 4K recording, more detail is apparent than would have been achieved from a native 2K recording.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Increased fineness and contrast is then possible with output to DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Some cinematographers record at 4K with the Super 35 film format to offset any resolution loss that may occur during video processing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Many consumer electronics such as mobile phones store video footage in Y′CBCR format with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling, which records color information at only one quarter the resolution as the brightness information.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] For 3840 × 2160 video, this means that the color information is only stored at 1920 × 1080.
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] Consumer cameras and mobile phones record 2160p footage at much higher bit rates (usually 50 to 100 Mbit/s) than 1080p (usually 10 to 30 Mbit/s).
[src:dnxhr-codec/4k-resolution] This higher bit rate reduces the visibility of compression artifacts, even if viewed on monitors with a lower resolution than 2160p.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] 8K display resolution is the successor to 4K resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] TV manufacturers pushed to make 4K a new standard by 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] At CES 2012, the first prototype 8K TVs were unveiled by Japanese electronics corporation Sharp.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The feasibility of a fast transition to this new standard is questionable in view of the absence of broadcasting resources.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 2018, Strategy Analytics predicted that 8K-ready devices will still only account for 3% of UHD TVs by 2023 with global sales of 11 million units a year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] However, TV manufacturers remain optimistic as the 4K market grew much faster than expected, with actual sales exceeding projections nearly six-fold in 2016.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 2013, a transmission network's capability to carry HDTV resolution was limited by internet speeds and relied on satellite broadcast to transmit the high data rates.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The demand is expected to drive the adoption of video compression standards and to place significant pressure on physical communication networks in the near future.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 2018, few cameras had the capability to shoot video in 8K, NHK being one of the few companies to have created a small broadcasting camera with an 8K image sensor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] By 2018, Red Digital Cinema camera company had delivered three 8K cameras in both a Full Frame sensor and Super 35 sensor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 1986, Sony introduced a smectic light valve LCD laser projector that could display high resolutions up to 8K resolution (8000×10,000).
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 1995, Japan's public broadcaster NHK was the first to start research and development of 4320p resolution, with the Super Hi-Vision system intended as a successor to their Hi-Vision HDTV system.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] 8K Ultra HDTV (UHDTV) was first demonstrated by NHK, JVC and Ikegami Tsushinki researchers with the Super Hi‑Vision system in January 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The format was standardized by SMPTE in October 2007.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The interface was standardized by SMPTE in August 2010 and recommended as the international standard for television by ITU-R in 2012.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Followed by public displays at electronics shows and screenings of 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi and public viewings in February 2014 and the FIFA World Cup in Brazil in June 2014 using HEVC with partners AstroDesign and Ikegami Electronics.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2015, the MHL Consortium announced the release of the superMHL specification which will support 8K resolution at 120 fps, 48-bit video, the Rec.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] 2020 color space, high dynamic range support, a 32-pin reversible superMHL connector, and power charging of up to 40 watts.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On March 1, 2016, the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) unveiled DisplayPort 1.4, a new format that allows the use of 8K resolution (7680 × 4320) at 60 Hz with HDRR and 32 audio channels through USB-C.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On January 4, 2017, the HDMI Forum announced HDMI 2.1 featuring support for 8K video with HDR, which will be "released early in Q2 2017".
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] 8K Association Formed at CES 2019 to Help Develop 8K Ecosystem.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In early February 2020, Samsung Electronics announced during their Unpacked event that their Samsung Galaxy S20 can video record in 8K, which uses 600 MB of storage per minute.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On April 6, 2013, Astrodesign Inc. announced the AH-4800, capable of recording 8K resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In April 2015, it was announced by Red that their newly unveiled Red Weapon VV is also capable of recording 8K footage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In October 2016, they announced two additional 8K cameras, Red Weapon 8K S35 and Red Epic-W 8K S35.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The Red Weapon Dragon VV has been discontinued as of October 7, 2017, when Red unveiled the Red Weapon Monstro VV, their fourth camera capable of shooting 8K, with additional improvements in dynamic range and noise reduction, among other features.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In May 2019, mobile phone vendors started releasing the first mobile phones with 8K video recording capabilities, such as the ZTE Nubia Red Magic 3 series.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] This is enabled by the sufficient resolution of image sensors used in mobile phones, and by the sufficient chipset performance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] However, mobile phones with up to 5K (2880p) or 6K (3240p) video cameras have never been released.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In 2007, the original 65 mm negative of the 1992 film *Baraka* was re-scanned at 8K with a film scanner built specifically for the job at FotoKem Laboratories, and used to remaster the 2008 Blu-ray release.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] According to Grover Crisp, executive VP of restoration at Sony Pictures, the new 8K scan has such high resolution that when examined, showed a series of fine concentric lines in a pattern "reminiscent of a fingerprint" near the top of the frame.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] This was caused by the film emulsion melting and cracking in the desert heat during production.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Sony had to hire a third party to minimize or eliminate the rippling artifacts in the new restored version.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On May 17, 2013, the Franklin Institute premiered *To Space and Back*, an 8K×8K, 60 fps, 3D video running approximately 25 minutes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] During its first run at the Fels Planetarium it was played at 4K, 60 fps.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In November 2013, NHK screened the experimental-drama short film "The Chorus" at Tokyo Film Festival which was filmed in 8K and 22.2 sound format.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On May 1, 2015, an 8K abstract computer animation was screened at the Filmatic Festival at the University of California, San Diego.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The work was created as an assignment in the VIS 40/ICAM 40 Introduction to Computing in the Arts class taught at UCSD by Associate Teaching Professor Brett Stalbaum during the winter quarter of 2015, with each student producing three hundred 8192 × 4800 pixel frames.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The work's music soundtrack was composed by Mark Matamoros.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2016, director James Gunn stated that the 2017 film *Guardians of the Galaxy Vol.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] 2* would be the first feature film to be shot in 8K, using the Red Weapon 8K VV.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The movie was shot with 8K cameras (and partially with 4K cameras), although the digital intermediate of the movie is in a lower resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Japanese public broadcaster NHK began research and development on 8K in 1995, having spent over $1 billion on R&D since then.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Codenamed *Super Hi-Vision* (named after its old Hi-Vision analog HDTV system), NHK also was simultaneously working on the development of 22.2 channel surround sound audio.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The world's first 8K television was unveiled by Sharp at the Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in 2012.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Ultimately, about 200 hours of material from the Tokyo Olympics, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were broadcast in 8K (on the NHK BS8K channel).
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The specification for an 8K Blu-ray format was also completed by the Blu-ray Disc Association for use in Japan by December 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] As of the end of 2024, there are no standalone Blu-ray players certified as 8K capable (even though PC Blu-ray drives able to read 100 GB and 128 GB discs are sold commercially), and no home video releases in 8K on physical media by any major studio.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] On December 1, 2018, NHK launched BS8K, a broadcast channel transmitting at 8K resolution.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Documentaries constitute a large part of that channel's programming.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Feature films shown in 8K on that channel include *2001: A Space Odyssey* (1968) and *My Fair Lady* (1964); in both cases, 70 mm analog prints were used as a basis for the remastered 8K version.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] New productions filmed with digital 8K cameras have also been aired in 8K on that channel; they include the Edo period drama *Kikyo – The Return* and the WWII dramas *Wife of a Spy* and *Gift of Fire*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In Germany, the third season of *Das Boot* (a historical drama TV series set on a Nazi submarine) was made available in 8K on the Samsung TV Plus streaming service.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] In China, the state-owned CMG conglomerate launched a TV channel broadcasting at 8K resolution, known as CCTV-8K.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] Test broadcasts started in 2021 while the official launch was in 2022.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The Sony PlayStation 5 Pro generates 8K graphics and output, making it the first and only game console to do so, though as of October 2025 no full 8K games for it have publicly released.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] The GeForce RTX 3090, released in September 2020 at an MSRP of $1499, was marketed by Nvidia as the first graphics card capable of 8K 60 fps HDR gaming, recording, and streaming with ShadowPlay on PCs.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] However, only its successor, the GeForce RTX 4090, is often regarded as the first graphics card to achieve playable frame rates at 8K in many modern titles.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] This is the resolution of the **UHDTV2** format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the **8K UHDTV** format defined in ITU-R BT.2020.
[src:dnxhr-codec/8k-resolution] It was also chosen by the DVB project as the resolution for their 8K broadcasting standard, **UHD-2**.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The original version of **Adobe Premiere** was one of the first computer-based non-linear video editing systems.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] It was released on Apple Mac in 1991 and for Microsoft Windows in September 1993.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The final version based on this codebase, version 6.5, was released in August 2002 for both Windows and Mac.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The software originated at SuperMac Technology under the name Reel Time, a QuickTime-based video editor developed for the company’s Video Spigot capture card.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] In August 1991, Adobe Systems acquired the project and rebranded it as Adobe Premiere.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Premiere was the second QuickTime-based video editor on the market.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Its ability to import new video formats could be enhanced by updating to a newer, compatible version of QuickTime.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] However, it could only process videos and images at a maximum width of 1,024 pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] In August 2003, Adobe released a substantial rewrite, and called it **Adobe Premiere Pro**.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Subsequent versions until 2026 were branded as Adobe Premiere Pro.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] On January 20, 2026, along with the version 26.0 launch, Adobe rebranded Adobe Premiere Pro back to the prior name **Adobe Premiere**, dropping the "Pro" suffix after 23 years of use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] This is the first time that Adobe Premiere has used the name without the suffix since its rebranding in 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The application continued to serve as Adobe's primary non-linear video editing system, and is still available to Creative Cloud users.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Adobe Premiere supports high-resolution video editing up to 10,240 × 8,192 pixels and 32-bit color depth in both RGB and YUV color spaces.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Key audio features include sample-level editing, support for VST plugins, and 5.1 surround sound mixing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The software is compatible with a wide range of video and audio formats and codecs on both macOS and Windows.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Using the Cineform Neo codec, it supports 3D editing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Adobe Premiere supports program files from Adobe Photoshop, Adobe Illustrator, and Adobe After Effects.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Adobe Premiere projects can also be imported into After Effects, and clips copied between the two applications retain most of their attributes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Projects from Premiere Rush are compatible with Adobe Premiere, allowing for advanced editing features and use of professional-grade tools.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The Adobe Premiere Pro and Adobe Premiere workflow integrates metadata across all stages of video production.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Adobe Story provides script integration functionality within the Adobe Premiere workflow, and Adobe OnLocation embeds metadata directly into the footage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Within Adobe Premiere, speech recognition technology analyzes audio and aligns it with the corresponding script dialogue using embedded metadata.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The Adobe Premiere family is a group of applications and services made by Adobe Inc. for the use of professional non-linear video editing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Supported features in these applications include metadata and ingest logging, media output encoding, and more.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] Adobe Premiere has been used in feature film production and is commonly used among video editors in online spaces.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] It is especially known for its integration with its companion application Adobe After Effects, which allowed it to become a prominent tool in the video editing space.
[src:dnxhr-codec/adobe-premiere-pro] The software is also widely recognized for its customizability, allowing for personalized organization of its modular panel design, each one serving a different purpose.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 was standardized by the ITU-T Video Coding Experts Group (VCEG) of Study Group 16 together with the ISO/IEC JTC 1 Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The project partnership effort is known as the Joint Video Team (JVT).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The ITU-T H.264 standard and the ISO/IEC MPEG-4 AVC standard (formally, ISO/IEC 14496-10 – MPEG-4 Part 10, Advanced Video Coding) are jointly maintained so that they have identical technical content.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The final drafting work on the first version of the standard was completed in May 2003, and various extensions of its capabilities have been added in subsequent editions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC), a.k.a.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.265 and MPEG-H Part 2 is a successor to H.264/MPEG-4 AVC developed by the same organizations, while earlier standards are still in common use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is perhaps best known as being the most commonly used video encoding format on Blu-ray Discs.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is restricted by patents owned by various parties.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A license covering most (but not all) patents essential to H.264 is administered by a patent pool formerly administered by MPEG LA.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Via Licensing Corp acquired MPEG LA in April 2023 and formed a new patent pool administration company called Via Licensing Alliance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The commercial use of patented H.264 technologies requires the payment of royalties to Via and other patent owners.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] MPEG LA has allowed the free use of H.264 technologies for streaming Internet video that is free to end users, and Cisco paid royalties to MPEG LA on behalf of the users of binaries for its open source H.264 encoder openH264.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The H.264 name follows the ITU-T naming convention, where Recommendations are given a letter corresponding to their series and a recommendation number within the series.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is part of "H-Series Recommendations: Audiovisual and multimedia systems".
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is further categorized into "H.200-H.499: Infrastructure of audiovisual services" and "H.260-H.279: Coding of moving video".
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The MPEG-4 AVC name relates to the naming convention in ISO/IEC MPEG, where the standard is part 10 of ISO/IEC 14496, which is the suite of standards known as MPEG-4.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standard was developed jointly in a partnership of VCEG and MPEG, after earlier development work in the ITU-T as a VCEG project called H.26L.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] It is thus common to refer to the standard with names such as H.264/AVC, AVC/H.264, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, or MPEG-4/H.264 AVC, to emphasize the common heritage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Occasionally, it is also referred to as "the JVT codec", in reference to the Joint Video Team (JVT) organization that developed it.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] (Such partnership and multiple naming is not uncommon.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, the video compression standard known as MPEG-2 also arose from the partnership between MPEG and the ITU-T, where MPEG-2 video is known to the ITU-T community as H.262.) Some software programs (such as VLC media player) internally identify this standard as AVC1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] VCEG was chaired by Gary Sullivan (Microsoft, formerly PictureTel, U.S.).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The first draft design for that new standard was adopted in August 1999.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In 2000, Thomas Wiegand (Heinrich Hertz Institute, Germany) became VCEG co-chair.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In December 2001, VCEG and the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG – ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 29/WG 11) formed a Joint Video Team (JVT), with the charter to finalize the video coding standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Formal approval of the specification came in March 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The JVT was (is) chaired by Gary Sullivan, Thomas Wiegand, and Ajay Luthra (Motorola, U.S.: later Arris, U.S.).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In July 2004, the Fidelity Range Extensions (FRExt) project was finalized.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] From January 2005 to November 2007, the JVT was working on an extension of H.264/AVC towards scalability by an Annex (G) called Scalable Video Coding (SVC).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The JVT management team was extended by Jens-Rainer Ohm (RWTH Aachen University, Germany).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] From July 2006 to November 2009, the JVT worked on Multiview Video Coding (MVC), an extension of H.264/AVC towards 3D television and limited-range free-viewpoint television.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] That work included the development of two new profiles of the standard: the Multiview High Profile and the Stereo High Profile.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Throughout the development of the standard, additional messages for containing supplemental enhancement information (SEI) have been developed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages can contain various types of data that indicate the timing of the video pictures or describe various properties of the coded video or how it can be used or enhanced.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages are also defined that can contain arbitrary user-defined data.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages do not affect the core decoding process, but can indicate how the video is recommended to be post-processed or displayed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Some other high-level properties of the video content are conveyed in video usability information (VUI), such as the indication of the color space for interpretation of the video content.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] As new color spaces have been developed, such as for high dynamic range and wide color gamut video, additional VUI identifiers have been added to indicate them.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standardization of the first version of H.264/AVC was completed in May 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In the first project to extend the original standard, the JVT then developed what was called the Fidelity Range Extensions (FRExt).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] These extensions enabled higher quality video coding by supporting increased sample bit depth precision and higher-resolution color information, including the sampling structures known as Y′CBCR 4:2:2 (a.k.a.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The design work on the FRExt project was completed in July 2004, and the drafting work on them was completed in September 2004.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The next major feature added to the standard was Scalable Video Coding (SVC).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Specified in Annex G of H.264/AVC, SVC allows the construction of bitstreams that contain *layers* of sub-bitstreams that also conform to the standard, including one such bitstream known as the "base layer" that can be decoded by a H.264/AVC codec that does not support SVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For temporal bitstream scalability (i.e., the presence of a sub-bitstream with a smaller temporal sampling rate than the main bitstream), complete access units are removed from the bitstream when deriving the sub-bitstream.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In this case, high-level syntax and inter-prediction reference pictures in the bitstream are constructed accordingly.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] On the other hand, for spatial and quality bitstream scalability (i.e. the presence of a sub-bitstream with lower spatial resolution/quality than the main bitstream), the NAL (Network Abstraction Layer) is removed from the bitstream when deriving the sub-bitstream.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] In this case, inter-layer prediction (i.e., the prediction of the higher spatial resolution/quality signal from the data of the lower spatial resolution/quality signal) is typically used for efficient coding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Scalable Video Coding extensions were completed in November 2007.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The next major feature added to the standard was Multiview Video Coding (MVC).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Specified in Annex H of H.264/AVC, MVC enables the construction of bitstreams that represent more than one view of a video scene.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] An important example of this functionality is stereoscopic 3D video coding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Two profiles were developed in the MVC work: Multiview High profile supports an arbitrary number of views, and Stereo High profile is designed specifically for two-view stereoscopic video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Multiview Video Coding extensions were completed in November 2009.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Additional extensions were later developed that included 3D video coding with joint coding of depth maps and texture (termed 3D-AVC), multi-resolution frame-compatible (MFC) stereoscopic and 3D-MFC coding, various additional combinations of features, and higher frame sizes and frame rates.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Versions of the H.264/AVC standard include the following completed revisions, corrigenda, and amendments (dates are final approval dates in ITU-T, while final "International Standard" approval dates in ISO/IEC are somewhat different and slightly later in most cases).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Each version represents changes relative to the next lower version that is integrated into the text.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The H.264 video format has a very broad application range that covers all forms of digital compressed video from low bit-rate Internet streaming applications to HDTV broadcast and Digital Cinema applications with nearly lossless coding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] With the use of H.264, bit rate savings of 50% or more compared to MPEG-2 Part 2 are reported.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, H.264 has been reported to give the same Digital Satellite TV quality as current MPEG-2 implementations with less than half the bitrate, with current MPEG-2 implementations working at around 3.5 Mbit/s and H.264 at only 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Sony claims that 9 Mbit/s AVC recording mode is equivalent to the image quality of the HDV format, which uses approximately 18–25 Mbit/s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] To ensure compatibility and problem-free adoption of H.264/AVC, many standards bodies have amended or added to their video-related standards so that users of these standards can employ H.264/AVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Both the Blu-ray Disc format and the now-discontinued HD DVD format include the H.264/AVC High Profile as one of three mandatory video compression formats.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Digital Video Broadcast project (DVB) approved the use of H.264/AVC for broadcast television in late 2004.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Advanced Television Systems Committee (ATSC) standards body in the United States approved the use of H.264/AVC for broadcast television in July 2008.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] It has also been approved for use with the more recent ATSC-M/H (Mobile/Handheld) standard, using the AVC and SVC portions of H.264.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The closed-circuit-television and video-surveillance markets have included the technology in many products.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Many common DSLRs use H.264 video wrapped in QuickTime MOV containers as the native recording format.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] AVCHD is a high-definition recording format designed by Sony and Panasonic that uses H.264 (conforming to H.264 while adding additional application-specific features and constraints).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] AVC-Intra is an intraframe-only compression format, developed by Panasonic.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC is a recording format designed by Sony that uses level 5.2 of H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, which is the highest level supported by that video standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC can support 4K resolution (4096 × 2160 and 3840 × 2160) at up to 60 frames per second (fps).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Sony has announced that cameras that support XAVC include two CineAlta cameras—the Sony PMW-F55 and Sony PMW-F5.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Sony PMW-F55 can record XAVC with 4K resolution at 30 fps at 300 Mbit/s and 2K resolution at 30 fps at 100 Mbit/s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC can record 4K resolution at 60 fps with 4:2:2 chroma sampling at 600 Mbit/s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264/AVC/MPEG-4 Part 10 contains a number of new features that allow it to compress video much more efficiently than older standards and to provide more flexibility for application to a wide variety of network environments.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] These techniques, along with several others, help H.264 to perform significantly better than any prior standard under a wide variety of circumstances in a wide variety of application environments.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 can often perform radically better than MPEG-2 video—typically obtaining the same quality at half of the bit rate or less, especially on high bit rate and high resolution video content.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Like other ISO/IEC MPEG video standards, H.264/AVC has a reference software implementation that can be freely downloaded.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Its main purpose is to give examples of H.264/AVC features, rather than being a useful application *per se*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Some reference hardware design work has also been conducted in the Moving Picture Experts Group.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The above-mentioned aspects include features in all profiles of H.264.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A profile for a codec is a set of features of that codec identified to meet a certain set of specifications of intended applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This means that many of the features listed are not supported in some profiles.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Various profiles of H.264/AVC are discussed in next section.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standard defines several sets of capabilities, which are referred to as *profiles*, targeting specific classes of applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] These are declared using a profile code (profile_idc) and sometimes a set of additional constraints applied in the encoder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The profile code and indicated constraints allow a decoder to recognize the requirements for decoding that specific bitstream.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] (And in many system environments, only one or two profiles are allowed to be used, so decoders in those environments do not need to be concerned with recognizing the less commonly used profiles.) By far the most commonly used profile is the High Profile.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily for low-cost applications, this profile is most typically used in videoconferencing and mobile applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] It corresponds to the subset of features that are in common between the Baseline, Main, and High Profiles.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily for low-cost applications that require additional data loss robustness, this profile is used in some videoconferencing and mobile applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile includes all features that are supported in the Constrained Baseline Profile, plus three additional features that can be used for loss robustness (or for other purposes such as low-delay multi-point video stream compositing).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The importance of this profile has faded somewhat since the definition of the Constrained Baseline Profile in 2009.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] All Constrained Baseline Profile bitstreams are also considered to be Baseline Profile bitstreams, as these two profiles share the same profile identifier code value.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Intended as the streaming video profile, this profile has relatively high compression capability and some extra tricks for robustness to data losses and server stream switching.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile is used for standard-definition digital TV broadcasts that use the MPEG-4 format as defined in the DVB standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] It is not, however, used for high-definition television broadcasts, as the importance of this profile faded when the High Profile was developed in 2004 for that application.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Similar to the High profile, but without support of field coding features.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Similar to the Progressive High profile, but without support of B (bi-predictive) slices.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Going beyond typical mainstream consumer product capabilities, this profile builds on top of the High Profile, adding support for up to 10 bits per sample of decoded picture precision.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] format while using up to 10 bits per sample of decoded picture precision.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile builds on top of the High 4:2:2 Profile, supporting up to 4:4:4 chroma sampling, up to 14 bits per sample, and additionally supporting efficient lossless region coding and the coding of each picture as three separate color planes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For camcorders, editing, and professional applications, the standard contains four additional Intra-frame-only profiles, which are defined as simple subsets of other corresponding profiles.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 10 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:2:2 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:4:4 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:4:4 Profile constrained to all-Intra use and to CAVLC entropy coding (i.e., not supporting CABAC).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting video conferencing, mobile, and surveillance applications, this profile builds on top of the Constrained Baseline profile to which the base layer (a subset of the bitstream) must conform.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For the scalability tools, a subset of the available tools is enabled.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A subset of the Scalable Baseline Profile intended primarily for real-time communication applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting broadcast and streaming applications, this profile builds on top of the H.264/AVC High Profile to which the base layer must conform.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A subset of the Scalable High Profile intended primarily for real-time communication applications.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting production applications, this profile is the Scalable High Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] 3D video and combines the tools of the High profile with the inter-view prediction capabilities of the MVC extension.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile supports two or more views using both inter-picture (temporal) and MVC inter-view prediction, but does not support field pictures and macroblock-adaptive frame-field coding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A profile for stereoscopic coding with two-layer resolution enhancement.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile supports joint coding of depth map and video texture information for improved compression of 3D video content.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] An enhanced profile for combined multiview coding with depth information.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] As the term is used in the standard, a "*level*" is a specified set of constraints that indicate a degree of required decoder performance for a profile.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, a level of support within a profile specifies the maximum picture resolution, frame rate, and bit rate that a decoder may use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] A decoder that conforms to a given level must be able to decode all bitstreams encoded for that level and all lower levels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The maximum bit rate for the High Profile is 1.25 times that of the Constrained Baseline, Baseline, Extended and Main Profiles; 3 times for Hi10P, and 4 times for Hi422P/Hi444PP.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The number of luma samples is 16×16=256 times the number of macroblocks (and the number of luma samples per second is 256 times the number of macroblocks per second).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Previously encoded pictures are used by H.264/AVC encoders to provide predictions of the values of samples in other pictures.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This allows the encoder to make efficient decisions on the best way to encode a given picture.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] At the decoder, such pictures are stored in a virtual *decoded picture buffer* (DPB).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] This formula is specified in sections A.3.1.h and A.3.2.f of the 2017 edition of the standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, for an HDTV picture that is 1,920 samples wide (PicWidthInMbs = 120) and 1,080 samples high (FrameHeightInMbs = 68), a Level 4 decoder has a maximum DPB storage capacity of floor(32768/(120*68)) = 4 frames (or 8 fields).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Thus, the value 4 is shown in parentheses in the table above in the right column of the row for Level 4 with the frame size 1920×1080.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] The current picture being decoded is *not included* in the computation of DPB fullness (unless the encoder has indicated for it to be stored for use as a reference for decoding other pictures or for delayed output timing).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p01] Thus, a decoder needs to actually have sufficient memory to handle (at least) one frame *more* than the maximum capacity of the DPB as calculated above.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2009, the HTML5 working group was split between supporters of Ogg Theora, a free video format which is thought to be unencumbered by patents, and H.264, which contains patented technology.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] As late as July 2009, Google and Apple were said to support H.264, while Mozilla and Opera support Ogg Theora (eventually Google, Mozilla and Opera all supported Theora and WebM with VP8, although Theora support was removed in 2023–2024).
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Microsoft, with the release of Internet Explorer 9, has added support for HTML 5 video encoded using H.264.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] On March 18, 2012, Mozilla announced support for H.264 in Firefox on mobile devices, due to prevalence of H.264-encoded video and the increased power-efficiency of using dedicated H.264 decoder hardware common on such devices.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] On February 20, 2013, Mozilla implemented support in Firefox for decoding H.264 on Windows 7 and above.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] This feature relies on Windows' built in decoding libraries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Firefox 35.0, released on January 13, 2015, supports H.264 on OS X 10.6 and higher.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] However, any software projects that use Cisco's source code instead of its binaries would be legally responsible for paying all royalties to MPEG LA.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Target CPU architectures include x86 and ARM, and target operating systems include Linux, Windows XP and later, Mac OS X, and Android; iOS was notably absent from this list, because it does not allow applications to fetch and install binary modules from the Internet.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Also on October 30, 2013, Brendan Eich from Mozilla wrote that it would use Cisco's binaries in future versions of Firefox to add support for H.264 to Firefox where platform codecs are not available.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Cisco published the source code to OpenH264 on December 9, 2013.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Although iOS was not supported by the 2013 Cisco software release, Apple updated its Video Toolbox Framework with iOS 8 (released in September 2014) to provide direct access to hardware-based H.264/AVC video encoding and decoding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Because H.264 encoding and decoding require significant computational power for specific arithmetic operations, software implementations running on general-purpose CPUs are typically less power-efficient.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] However, consumer-grade CPUs with 6 or 8 cores since around 2016, and quad-core general-purpose x86 CPUs as of January 2020 have sufficient computation power to perform real-time SD and HD encoding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Compression efficiency depends on video algorithmic implementations, not on whether hardware or software implementation is used.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Therefore, the difference between hardware and software based implementation is more on power-efficiency, flexibility and cost.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] To improve the power efficiency and reduce hardware form-factor, special-purpose hardware may be employed, either for the complete encoding or decoding process, or for acceleration assistance within a CPU-controlled environment.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] CPU based solutions are known to be much more flexible, particularly when encoding must be done concurrently in multiple formats, multiple bit rates and resolutions (multi-screen video), and possibly with additional features on container format support, advanced integrated advertising features, etc.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] CPU based software solution generally makes it much easier to load balance multiple concurrent encoding sessions within the same CPU.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] The 2nd generation Intel "Sandy Bridge" Core i3/i5/i7 processors introduced at the January 2011 CES (Consumer Electronics Show) offer an on-chip hardware full HD H.264 encoder, known as Intel Quick Sync Video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] A hardware H.264 encoder can be an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Some companies have both FPGA and ASIC product offerings.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] Texas Instruments manufactures a line of ARM + DSP cores that perform DSP H.264 BP encoding 1080p at 30 fps.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] This permits flexibility with respect to codecs (which are implemented as highly optimized DSP code) while being more efficient than software on a generic CPU.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In countries where patents on software algorithms are upheld, vendors and commercial users of products that use H.264/AVC are expected to pay patent licensing royalties for the patented technology that their products use.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] This applies to the Baseline Profile as well.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] A private organization known as Via-LA administers the licenses for patents applying to this standard, as well as other patent pools, such as for MPEG-4 Part 2 Video, HEVC and MPEG-DASH.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] On August 26, 2010, MPEG-LA announced that royalties would not be charged for H.264 encoded Internet video that is free to end users.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] All other royalties remain in place, such as royalties for products that decode and encode H.264 video as well as to operators of free television and subscription channels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] The license terms are updated in 5-year blocks.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2005, Qualcomm sued Broadcom in US District Court, alleging that Broadcom infringed on two of its patents by making products that were compliant with the H.264 video compression standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2007, the District Court found that the patents were unenforceable because Qualcomm had failed to disclose them to the JVT prior to the release of the H.264 standard in May 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In December 2008, the US Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit affirmed the District Court's order that the patents be unenforceable but remanded to the District Court with instructions to limit the scope of unenforceability to H.264 compliant products.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In October 2023 Nokia sued HP and Amazon for H.264/H.265 patent infringement in USA, UK and other locations.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] In February 2026, the VIA Licensing Authority announced a new licensing scheme targeting video streaming that applies to version 4 of the h264 specification and later.
[src:dnxhr-codec/advanced-video-coding-p02] This changes the terms for new licensees after January 2026.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was founded at the mouth of the Amstel river, which was dammed to control flooding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Originally a small fishing village in the 12th century, Amsterdam became a major world port during the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century, when the Netherlands was an economic powerhouse.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was the leading centre for finance and trade, as well as a hub of secular art production.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded and new neighborhoods and suburbs were built.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city has a long tradition of openness, liberalism, and tolerance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Cycling is key to the city's modern character, and there are numerous biking paths and lanes spread throughout.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city is known for its nightlife and festival activity, with several nightclubs among the world's most famous.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Its artistic heritage, canals, and narrow canal houses with gabled façades, well-preserved legacies of the city's 17th-century Golden Age, have attracted millions of visitors annually.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange, founded in 1602, is considered the oldest "modern" securities market stock exchange in the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] As the commercial capital of the Netherlands and one of the top financial centres in Europe, Amsterdam is considered an alpha-world city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city is the cultural capital of the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many large Dutch institutions have their headquarters in the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many of the world's largest companies are based in Amsterdam or have established their European headquarters there, such as technology companies Uber, Netflix, and Tesla.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Although Amsterdam is the official capital of the Netherlands, it is not the seat of government.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The main governmental institutions, and foreign embassies, are located in The Hague.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 2022, Amsterdam was ranked the ninth-best city to live in by the Economist Intelligence Unit and 12th on quality of living for environment and infrastructure by Mercer.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city was ranked 4th place globally as a top tech hub in 2019.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Port of Amsterdam is the fifth largest in Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The KLM hub and Amsterdam's main airport, Schiphol, is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and third in Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch capital is one of the most multicultural cities in the world, with about 180 nationalities represented.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Immigration and ethnic segregation in Amsterdam is a current issue.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's notable residents throughout its history include painters Rembrandt and Vincent van Gogh, 17th-century philosophers Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, René Descartes, and John Amos Comenius, and Holocaust victim and diarist Anne Frank.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Due to its geographical location in what used to be wet peatland, the founding of Amsterdam is later than other urban centres in the Low Countries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] However, around the area of what later became Amsterdam, farmers settled as early as three millennia ago.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] They lived along the prehistoric IJ river and upstream of its tributary Amstel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The prehistoric IJ was a shallow and quiet stream in peatland behind beach ridges.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This secluded area was able to grow into an important local settlement centre, especially in the late Bronze Age, the Iron Age and the Roman Age.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Until water issues were controlled, a permanent settlement would not have been possible, since the river mouth and the banks of the Amstel in this period in time were too wet for permanent habitation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The origins of Amsterdam are linked to the development of a dam on the Amstel River called *Amestelle*, meaning 'watery area', from *Aa(m)* 'river' + *stelle* 'site at a shoreline', 'river bank'.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In this area, land reclamation started as early as the late 10th century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was located along a side arm of the IJ.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This sidearm took its name from the eponymous land: Amstel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was inhabited by farmers, who lived more inland and more upstream, where the land was not as wet as at the banks of the downstream river mouth.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These farmers were starting the reclamation around upstream Ouderkerk aan de Amstel, and later at the other side of the river at Amstelveen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Van Amstel family, known in documents by this name since 1019, held the stewardship in this northwestern nook of the ecclesiastical district of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The family later served also under the count of Holland.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A major turning point in the development of the Amstel River mouth was the All Saint's Flood of 1170.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In an extremely short time, the shallow river IJ turned into a wide estuary, which from then on offered the Amstel an open connection to the Zuiderzee, IJssel, and waterways further afield.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This made the water flow of the Amstel more active, so excess water could be drained better.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] With drier banks, the downstream Amstel mouth became attractive for permanent habitation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Moreover, the river had grown from an insignificant peat stream into a junction of international waterways.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A settlement was built here immediately after the landscape change of 1170.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Right from the start of its foundation it focused on traffic, production, and trade; not on farming, as opposed to how communities had lived further upstream for the past 200 years and northward for thousands of years.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The construction of a dam at the mouth of the Amstel, eponymously named Dam, is historically estimated to have occurred between 1264 and 1275.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The settlement first appeared in a document from 1275, concerning a road toll granted by the count of Holland Floris V to the residents *apud Amestelledamme* 'at the dam in the Amstel' or 'at the dam of Amstelland'.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This allowed the inhabitants of the village to travel freely through the County of Holland, paying no tolls at bridges, locks and dams.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This was a move in a years-long struggle for power in the area between the count of Holland and the Amstel family who governed the area on behalf of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] By 1327, the name had developed into *Aemsterdam*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The bishop of Utrecht granted Amsterdam zone rights in either 1300 or 1306.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Mirakel van Amsterdam in 1345 rendered the city an important place of pilgrimage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During the heyday of the *Stille Omgang*, which became the expression of the pilgrimage after the Protestant Reformation, up to 90,000 pilgrims came to Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] From the 14th century on, Amsterdam flourished, largely from trade with the Hanseatic League.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] From the 15th century on the city established an independent trade route with the Baltic Sea in grain and timber, cutting out the Hanseatic League as middlemen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city became the staple market of Europe for bulk cargo.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This was made possible due to innovations in the herring fishery, from which Amsterdam reaped great wealth.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Herring had demand in markets all around Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Inventions of on-board gibbing and the haringbuis in 1415, made longer voyages feasible and hence enabled Dutch fishermen to follow the herring shoals far from the coasts, giving them a monopoly in the industry.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The herring industry relied on international trade cooperation and large initial investments in ships.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This required many highly skilled and unskilled workers to cooperate, as well as the import of the necessary raw materials to turn an unfinished product into a marketable one.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This required merchants to then sell it throughout the continent and bookkeepers and accountants to divide the profit.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In short, the herring industry was setting up the foundations for what would later become the transcontinental trade system and the Dutch Golden Age, with Amsterdam at its centre, hence the saying "Amsterdam is built on Herringbones".
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Low Countries were part of the Habsburg inheritance and came under the Spanish Empire in the early sixteenth century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch rebelled against Philip II of Spain, who led a defense of Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The main reasons for the uprising were the imposition of new taxes, the tenth penny, and the religious persecution of Protestants by the newly introduced Inquisition.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The revolt escalated into the Eighty Years' War, which ultimately led to Dutch independence.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Strongly pushed by Dutch Revolt leader William the Silent, the Dutch Republic became known for its relative religious tolerance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Jews from the Iberian Peninsula, Protestant Huguenots from France, prosperous merchants, and printers from Flanders, and economic and religious refugees from the Spanish-controlled parts of the Low Countries found safety in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The influx of Flemish printers and the city's intellectual tolerance made Amsterdam a centre for the European free press.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced what is considered its *Golden Age*, during which it became the wealthiest city in the Western world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Ships sailed from Amsterdam to the Baltic Sea, the Caribbean, North America, and Africa, as well as present-day Indonesia, India, Sri Lanka, and Brazil, forming the basis of a worldwide trading network.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's merchants had the largest share in both the Dutch East India Company (VOC) and the Dutch West India Company.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These companies acquired overseas possessions that later became Dutch colonies.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was Europe's most important hub for the shipment of goods and was the leading financial centre of the Western world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1602, the Amsterdam office of the Dutch East India Company became the world's first stock exchange by trading in its own shares.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Bank of Amsterdam started operations in 1609, acting as a full-service bank for Dutch merchant bankers and as a reserve bank.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] From the 17th century onwards, Amsterdam also became involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city was a major destination port for Dutch slave ships participating in the triangular trade, which lasted until the United Netherlands abolished the Netherlands' involvement in the trade in 1814 at the request of the British government.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's prosperity declined during the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The wars of the Dutch Republic with England (latterly, Great Britain) and France took their toll on the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars and the Napoleonic Wars, Amsterdam's significance reached its lowest point, with Holland being absorbed into the French Empire.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] However, the later establishment of the United Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1815 marked a turning point.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The end of the 19th century is sometimes called Amsterdam's second Golden Age.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] New museums, a railway station, and the Concertgebouw were built; At the same time, the Industrial Revolution reached the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam–Rhine Canal was dug to give Amsterdam a direct connection to the Rhine, and the North Sea Canal was dug to give the port a shorter connection to the North Sea.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Both projects dramatically improved commerce with the rest of Europe and the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1906, Joseph Conrad gave a brief description of Amsterdam as seen from the seaside, in *The Mirror of the Sea*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Shortly before the First World War, the city started to expand again, and new suburbs were built.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Even though the Netherlands remained neutral in this war, Amsterdam suffered a food shortage, and heating fuel became scarce.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The shortages sparked riots in which several people were killed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These riots are known as the *Aardappeloproer* (Potato Rebellion).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] People started looting stores and warehouses to get supplies, mainly food.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] On 1 January 1921, after a flood in 1916, the depleted municipalities of Durgerdam, Holysloot, Zunderdorp and Schellingwoude (all lying north of Amsterdam) were, at their own request, annexed to the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Between the wars, the city continued to expand, most notably to the west of the Jordaan district in the Frederik Hendrikbuurt and surrounding neighbourhoods.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Nazi Germany invaded the Netherlands on 10 May 1940 and took control of the country.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Some Amsterdam citizens sheltered Jews, thereby exposing themselves and their families to a high risk of being imprisoned or sent to concentration camps.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] More than 100,000 Dutch Jews were deported and murdered in Nazi concentration camps, including 56,521 victims in Auschwitz and a further number of 34,082 accounted for in Sobibor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Around 60,000 Jewish inhabitants, including Jewish prewar refugees from Austria and Germany, were living in Amsterdam at the time of the Nazi occupation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Only those provided with a safe haven, avoiding deportation and denunciation, or the very few who returned from the camps at the end of the war, managed to survive.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] At first the German occupation authorities were very cautious, wanting to convince the city inhabitants of their sincerity.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] However, their outlook soon turned to cynicism and brutality.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A cause in the change of their behaviour was an attack by a Dutch resistance fighter against a collaborator belonging to the paramilitary Dutch fascist organisation, the NSB.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The injured man died and in response Heinrich Himmler ordered reprisals.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] 427 Amsterdam Jews were arrested on 22 February 1941 and sent to Mauthausen concentration camp.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Incensed, a broad spectrum of passive resistance was organized by the Dutch Underground.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Trade unions, among them socialist and Communist Party activists, led the protest.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Their outcry received support from white collar employees in the civil service and support from the local diocese of the Church.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Approval was also given and encouraged by the Dutch government-in-exile under Queen Wilhelmina in London.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The German authorities were taken completely by surprise by the level of resistance known as the February strike.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] 300,000 people participated in the protest against the arrests of Jews.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] However, the occupier soon responded crudely and brutally, smashing union and illegal party activity.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] With the edifice of resistance removed the SS and German police apparatus, supported by collaborators in the Dutch auxiliary police, arrested thousands of defenceless Jews in Amsterdam's Jewish Quarter.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The two main waves of arrest, culminating in deportation, occurred on 26 May 1943 and on 20 June 1943.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The most famous deportee was the young Jewish girl Anne Frank, whose safe hiding place with her family was betrayed and discovered in August, 1944.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] After a spell at the 'holding camp' in Westerbork Anna and her family were sent to Auschwitz, where her mother was murdered.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] From there she and her sister Margot were moved onto Bergen-Belsen concentration camp where they died amidst appalling and inhumane conditions in early 1945.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the Second World War, and as a consequence of the Nazi occupation, Amsterdam was in a state of crisis.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Communication with the rest of the country broke down, and food and fuel became scarce.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many citizens traveled to the countryside to forage.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Dogs, cats, raw sugar beets, and tulip bulbs—cooked to a pulp—were consumed to stay alive.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many trees in Amsterdam were cut down for fuel, and wood was taken from the houses, apartments and other buildings of deported Jews.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city was finally liberated by Canadian forces on 5 May 1945, shortly before the end of the war in Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many new suburbs, such as Osdorp, Slotervaart, Slotermeer and Geuzenveld, were built in the years after the Second World War.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These suburbs contained many public parks and wide-open spaces, and the new buildings provided improved housing conditions with larger and brighter rooms, gardens, and balconies.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Because of the war and other events of the 20th century, almost the entire city centre had fallen into disrepair.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] As society was changing, politicians and other influential figures made plans to redesign large parts of it.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] There was an increasing demand for office buildings, and also for new roads, as the automobile became available to most people.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A metro started operating in 1977 between the new suburb of Bijlmermeer in the city's Zuidoost (southeast) exclave and the centre of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Further plans were to build a new highway above the metro to connect Amsterdam Centraal and the city centre with other parts of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The required large-scale demolitions began in Amsterdam's former Jewish neighborhood.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Smaller streets, such as the Jodenbreestraat and Weesperstraat, were widened and almost all houses and buildings were demolished.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] At the peak of the demolition, the *Nieuwmarktrellen* (Nieuwmarkt riots) broke out; the rioters expressed their fury about the demolition caused by the restructuring of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] As a result, the demolition was stopped and the highway into the city's centre was never fully built; only the metro was completed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The new city hall was built on the almost completely demolished Waterlooplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Meanwhile, large private organizations, such as *Stadsherstel Amsterdam*, were founded to restore the entire city centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Although the success of this struggle is visible today, efforts for further restoration are still ongoing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The entire city centre has reattained its former splendour and, as a whole, is now a protected area.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Many of its buildings have become monuments, and in July 2010 the Grachtengordel (the three concentric canals: Herengracht, Keizersgracht, and Prinsengracht) was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 21st century, the Amsterdam city centre has attracted large numbers of tourists: between 2012 and 2015, the annual number of visitors rose from 10 to 17 million.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Real estate prices have surged, and local shops are making way for tourist-oriented ones, making the centre unaffordable for the city's inhabitants.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These developments have evoked comparisons with Venice, a city thought to be overwhelmed by the tourist influx.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Construction of a new metro line connecting the part of the city north of the IJ to its southern part was started in 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The project was controversial because its cost had exceeded its budget by a factor of three by 2008, because of fears of damage to buildings in the centre, and because construction had to be halted and restarted multiple times.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The new metro line was completed in 2018.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Since 2014, renewed focus has been given to urban regeneration and renewal, especially in areas directly bordering the city centre, such as Frederik Hendrikbuurt.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This urban renewal and expansion of the traditional centre of the city—with the construction of artificial islands of the new eastern IJburg neighbourhood—is part of the Structural Vision Amsterdam 2040 initiative.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is located in the Western Netherlands, in the province of North Holland, the capital of which is not Amsterdam, but rather Haarlem.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The river Amstel ends in the city centre and connects to a large number of canals that eventually terminate in the IJ.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's elevation is about −2 m (−6.6 ft) below sea level.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The surrounding land is flat as it is formed of large polders.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] An artificial forest, Amsterdamse Bos, is in the southwest.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is connected to the North Sea by the North Sea Canal.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is intensely urbanised, as is the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam surrounding the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Comprising 219.4 km2 (84.7 sq mi) of land, the city proper has 4,457 inhabitants per km2 and 2,275 houses per km2.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Parks and nature reserves make up 12% of Amsterdam's land area.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has more than 100 km (60 mi) of canals, most of which are navigable by boat.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city's three main canals are the Prinsengracht, the Herengracht, and the Keizersgracht.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the Middle Ages, Amsterdam was surrounded by a moat, called the Singel, which now forms the innermost ring in the city, and gives the city centre a horseshoe shape.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] It has been compared with Venice, due to its division into about 90 islands, which are linked by more than 1,200 bridges.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*) strongly influenced by its proximity to the North Sea to the west, with prevailing westerly winds.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam, as well as most of the North Holland province, lies in USDA Hardiness zone 8b.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Frosts mainly occur during spells of easterly or northeasterly winds from the inner European continent.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Even then, because Amsterdam is surrounded on three sides by large bodies of water, as well as having a significant heat-island effect, nights rarely fall below −5 °C (23 °F), while it could easily be −12 °C (10 °F) in Hilversum, 25 km (16 mi) southeast.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Summers are moderately warm with several hot and humid days with occasional rain every month.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The average daily high in August is 22.1 °C (72 °F), and 30 °C (86 °F) or higher is only measured on average on 2.5 days, placing Amsterdam in AHS Heat Zone 2.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Days with more than 1 mm (0.04 in) of precipitation are common, on average 133 days per year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's average annual precipitation is 838 mm (33 in).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A large part of this precipitation falls as light rain or brief showers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Cloudy and damp days are common during the cooler months of October through March.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1300, Amsterdam's population was around 1,000 people.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] While many towns in Holland experienced population decline during the 15th and 16th centuries, Amsterdam's population grew, mainly due to the rise of the profitable Baltic maritime trade especially in grain after the Burgundian victory in the Dutch–Hanseatic War in 1441.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The population of Amsterdam was only modest compared to the towns and cities of Flanders and Brabant, which comprised the most urbanized area of the Low Countries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This changed when, during the Dutch Revolt, many people from the Southern Netherlands fled to the North, especially after Antwerp fell to Spanish forces in 1585.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Jews from Spain, Portugal, and Eastern Europe similarly settled in Amsterdam, as did Germans and Scandinavians.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In thirty years, Amsterdam's population more than doubled between 1585 and 1610.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During the 1660s, Amsterdam's population reached 200,000.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city's growth levelled off and the population stabilized around 240,000 for most of the 18th century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1750, Amsterdam was the fourth largest city in Western Europe, behind London (676,000), Paris (560,000) and Naples (324,000).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This was all the more remarkable as Amsterdam was neither the capital city nor the seat of government of the Dutch Republic, which itself was a much smaller state than Great Britain, France or the Ottoman Empire.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In contrast to those other metropolises, Amsterdam was also surrounded by large towns such as Leiden (about 67,000), Rotterdam (45,000), Haarlem (38,000), and Utrecht (30,000).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city's population declined in the early 19th century, dipping under 200,000 in 1820.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] By the second half of the 19th century, industrialization spurred renewed growth.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's population hit an all-time high of 872,000 in 1959, before declining in the following decades due to government-sponsored suburbanisation to so-called *groeikernen* (growth centres) such as Purmerend and Almere.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Between 1970 and 1980, Amsterdam experienced a sharp population decline, peaking at a net loss of 25,000 people in 1973.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] By 1985 the city had only 675,570 residents.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This was soon followed by reurbanization and gentrification, leading to renewed population growth in the 2010s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Also in the 2010s, much of Amsterdam's population growth was due to immigration to the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th and 17th centuries, non-Dutch immigrants to Amsterdam were mostly Protestant Huguenots and Flemings, Sephardic Jews, and Westphalians.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Huguenots came after the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, while the Flemish Protestants came during the Eighty Years' War against Catholic Spain.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Westphalians came to Amsterdam mostly for economic reasons; their influx continued through the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Before the Second World War, 10% of the city population was Jewish.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Just twenty percent of them survived the Holocaust.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam experienced an influx of religions and cultures after the Second World War.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] With 180 different nationalities, Amsterdam is home to one of the widest varieties of nationalities of any city in the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The proportion of the population of immigrant origin in the city proper is about 50% and 88% of the population are Dutch citizens.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The first mass immigration in the 20th century was by people from Indonesia, who came to Amsterdam after the independence of the Dutch East Indies in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 1960s guest workers from Turkey, Morocco, Italy, and Spain immigrated to Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] After the independence of Suriname in 1975, a large wave of Surinamese settled in Amsterdam, mostly in the Bijlmer area.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Other immigrants, including refugees asylum seekers and undocumented immigrants, came from Europe, the Americas, Asia, and Africa.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, many 'old' Amsterdammers moved to 'new' cities like Almere and Purmerend, prompted by the third Land-use planning bill of the Dutch Government.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This bill promoted suburbanization and arranged for new developments in so-called "groeikernen", literally *cores of growth*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Young professionals and artists moved into neighborhoods De Pijp and the Jordaan abandoned by these Amsterdammers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The non-Western immigrants settled mostly in the social housing projects in Amsterdam-West and the Bijlmer.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 2006, people of non-Western origin made up approximately one-fifth of the population of Amsterdam, and more than 30% of the city's children.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A slight majority of the residents of Amsterdam have at least one parent who was born outside the country.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] However, a much larger majority has at least one parent who was born inside the country (intercultural marriages are common in the city).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Only a third of inhabitants under 15 are *autochthons (*person with two parents of Dutch origin).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 2023, *autochthons* were a minority in 40% of Amsterdam's neighborhoods.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Segregation along ethnic lines is visible, with people of non-Western origin, considered a separate group by Statistics Netherlands, concentrating in specific neighborhoods especially in Nieuw-West, Zeeburg, Bijlmer and in certain areas of Amsterdam-Noord.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 2000, Christians formed the largest religious group in the city (28% of the population).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The next largest religion was Islam (8%), most of whose followers were Sunni.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] By 2015, this remained largely unchanged, with a slight decrease in the Muslim population to 7.1%.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has been one of the municipalities in the Netherlands that provided immigrants with extensive and free Dutch-language courses, which have benefited many immigrants.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1578, the largely Catholic city of Amsterdam joined the revolt against Spanish rule, late in comparison to other major northern Dutch cities.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Catholic priests were driven out of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Following the Dutch takeover, all churches were converted to Protestant worship.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Calvinism was declared the main religion.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] It was forbidden to openly profess Roman Catholicism and the Catholic hierarchy was prohibited until the mid-19th century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of clandestine churches, covert religious buildings hidden in pre-existing buildings.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Catholics, some Jews, and dissenting Protestants worshipped in such buildings.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A large influx of foreigners of many religions came to 17th-century Amsterdam, in particular Sephardic Jews from Spain and Portugal, Huguenots from France, Lutherans, Mennonites, as well as Protestants from across the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of many non-Dutch-speaking churches.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1603, the Jewish received permission to practice their religion in the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1639, the first synagogue was consecrated.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Jews came to call the town "Jerusalem of the West".
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] As they became established in the city, other Christian denominations used converted Catholic chapels to conduct their own services.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The oldest English-language church congregation in the world outside the United Kingdom is found at the Begijnhof.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Regular services there are still offered in English under the auspices of the Church of Scotland.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Being Calvinists, the Huguenots soon integrated into the Dutch Reformed Church, though often retaining their own congregations.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Some, commonly referred to by the moniker 'Walloon', are recognizable today as they offer occasional services in French.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the second half of the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced an influx of Ashkenazim, Jews from Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Jews often fled the pogroms in those areas.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The first Ashkenazis who arrived in Amsterdam were refugees from the Khmelnytsky uprising occurring in Ukraine and the Thirty Years' War, which devastated much of Central Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] They not only founded their own synagogues but had a strong influence on the 'Amsterdam dialect' adding a large Yiddish local vocabulary.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Despite an absence of an official Jewish ghetto, most Jews preferred to live in the eastern part, which used to be the centre of medieval Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The main street of this Jewish neighbourhood was Jodenbreestraat.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood comprised the Waterlooplein and the Nieuwmarkt.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Buildings in this neighbourhood fell into disrepair after the Second World War a large section of the neighbourhood was demolished during the construction of the metro system.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This led to riots, and as a result, the original plans for large-scale reconstruction were abandoned by the government.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood was rebuilt with smaller-scale residence buildings based on its original layout.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Catholic churches in Amsterdam have been constructed since the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy in 1853.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] One of the principal architects behind the city's Catholic churches, Cuypers, was also responsible for the Amsterdam Centraal station and the Rijksmuseum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1924, the Catholic Church hosted the International Eucharistic Congress in Amsterdam; numerous Catholic prelates visited the city, where festivities were held in churches and stadiums.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Catholic processions on the public streets, however, were still forbidden under law at the time.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Only in the 20th century was Amsterdam's relation to Catholicism normalised, but despite its far larger population size, the episcopal see of the city was placed in the provincial town of Haarlem.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Historically, Amsterdam has been predominantly Christian.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In 1900 about 70% of the city's population was Christian; the largest religious denomination was the Dutch Reformed Church, adhered to by about 45% of residents, while members of the Catholic Church formed 25%.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In recent times, the city's religious demography has diversified due to immigration from former colonies.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Hinduism has been introduced by immigrants from Suriname and several distinct branches of Islam have been brought from various parts of the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Islam is now the largest non-Christian religion in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The large community of Ghanaian immigrants has established African churches, often in parking garages in the Bijlmer area.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam fans out south from the Amsterdam Centraal station and Damrak, the main street off the station.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The oldest area of the town is known as De Wallen (English: "The Quays").
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] It lies to the east of Damrak and contains the city's famous red-light district.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] To the south of De Wallen is the old Jewish quarter of Waterlooplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The medieval and colonial age canals of Amsterdam, known as *grachten*, embraces the heart of the city where homes have interesting gables.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Beyond the Grachtengordel are the former working-class areas of Jordaan and de Pijp.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Museumplein with the city's major museums, the Vondelpark, a 19th-century park named after the Dutch writer Joost van den Vondel, as well as the Plantage neighbourhood, with the zoo, are also located outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Several parts of the city and the surrounding urban area are polders.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This can be recognised by the suffix *-meer* which means *lake*, as in Aalsmeer, Bijlmermeer, Haarlemmermeer and Watergraafsmeer.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam canal system is the result of conscious city planning.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the early 17th century, when immigration was at a peak, a comprehensive plan was developed that was based on four concentric half-circles of canals with their ends emerging at the IJ bay.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The fourth and outermost canal is the Singelgracht, which is often not mentioned on maps because it is a collective name for all canals in the outer ring.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Singelgracht should not be confused with the oldest and innermost canal, the Singel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The canals served for defense, water management and transport.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The defenses took the form of a moat and earthen dikes, with gates at transit points, but otherwise no masonry superstructures.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The original plans have been lost, so historians, such as Ed Taverne, need to speculate on the original intentions: it is thought that the considerations of the layout were purely practical and defensive rather than ornamental.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Construction started in 1613 and proceeded from west to east, across the breadth of the layout, like a gigantic windshield wiper as the historian Geert Mak calls it – and not from the centre outwards, as a popular myth has it.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The canal construction in the southern sector was completed by 1656.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Subsequently, the construction of residential buildings proceeded slowly.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The eastern part of the concentric canal plan, covering the area between the Amstel River and the IJ Bay, has never been implemented.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the following centuries, the land was used for parks, senior citizens' homes, theatres, other public facilities, and waterways without much planning.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Over the years, several canals have been filled in, becoming streets or squares, such as the Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal and the Spui.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] After the development of Amsterdam's canals in the 17th century, the city did not grow beyond its borders for two centuries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During the 19th century, Samuel Sarphati devised a plan based on the grandeur of Paris and London at that time.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The plan envisaged the construction of new houses, public buildings, and streets just outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The main aim of the plan, however, was to improve public health.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Although the plan did not expand the city, it did produce some of the largest public buildings to date, like the *Paleis voor Volksvlijt*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Following Sarphati, civil engineers Jacobus van Niftrik and Jan Kalff designed an entire ring of 19th-century neighbourhoods surrounding the city's centre, with the city preserving the ownership of all land outside the 17th-century limit, thus firmly controlling development.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Most of these neighbourhoods became home to the working class.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In response to overcrowding, two plans were designed at the beginning of the 20th century which were very different from anything Amsterdam had ever seen before: *Plan Zuid* (designed by the architect Berlage) and *West*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These plans involved the development of new neighbourhoods consisting of housing blocks for all social classes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] After the Second World War, large new neighbourhoods were built in the western, southeastern, and northern parts of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These new neighbourhoods were built to relieve the city's shortage of living space and give people affordable houses with modern conveniences.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhoods consisted mainly of large housing blocks located among green spaces, connected to wide roads, making the neighbourhoods accessible by motor car.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The western suburbs which were built in that period are collectively called the Westelijke Tuinsteden.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The area to the southeast of the city built during the same period is known as the Bijlmer.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has a rich architectural history.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The oldest building in Amsterdam is the Oude Kerk (English: Old Church), at the heart of the Wallen, consecrated in 1306.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The oldest wooden building is *Het Houten Huys* at the Begijnhof.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] It was constructed around 1425 and is one of only two existing wooden buildings.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] It is also one of the few examples of Gothic architecture in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The oldest stone building in the Netherlands, The Moriaan is built in 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th century, wooden buildings were razed and replaced with brick ones.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] During this period, many buildings were constructed in the architectural style of the Renaissance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Buildings of this period are very recognisable with their stepped gable façades, which is the common Dutch Renaissance style.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam quickly developed its own Renaissance architecture.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] These buildings were built according to the principles of the architect Hendrick de Keyser.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] One of the most striking buildings designed by Hendrick de Keyser is the Westerkerk.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the 17th century baroque architecture became very popular, as it was elsewhere in Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This roughly coincided with Amsterdam's Golden Age.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The leading architects of this style in Amsterdam were Jacob van Campen, Philips Vingboons and Daniel Stalpaert.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Philip Vingboons designed splendid merchants' houses throughout the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A famous building in baroque style in Amsterdam is the Royal Palace on Dam Square.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Throughout the 18th century, Amsterdam was heavily influenced by French culture.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] This is reflected in the architecture of that period.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Around 1815, architects broke with the baroque style and started building in different neo-styles.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Most Gothic style buildings date from that era and are therefore said to be built in a neo-gothic style.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the 19th century, the Jugendstil or Art Nouveau style became popular and many new buildings were constructed in this architectural style.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Since Amsterdam expanded rapidly during this period, new buildings adjacent to the city centre were also built in this style.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The houses in the vicinity of the Museum Square in Amsterdam Oud-Zuid are an example of Jugendstil.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The last style that was popular in Amsterdam before the modern era was Art Deco.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam had its own version of the style, which was called the Amsterdamse School.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Whole districts were built in this style, such as the *Rivierenbuurt*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] A notable feature of the façades of buildings designed in Amsterdamse School is that they are highly decorated and ornate, with oddly shaped windows and doors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The old city centre is the focal point of all the architectural styles before the end of the 19th century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Jugendstil and Georgian are mostly found outside the city centre in the neighbourhoods built in the early 20th century, although there are also some striking examples of these styles in the city centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Most historic buildings in the city centre and nearby are houses, such as the famous merchants' houses lining the canals.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has many parks, open spaces, and squares throughout the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Vondelpark, the largest park in the city, is located in the Oud-Zuid neighbourhood and is named after the 17th-century Amsterdam author Joost van den Vondel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Yearly, the park has around 10 million visitors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the park is an open-air theatre, a playground, and several horeca facilities.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] In the Zuid borough, is the Beatrixpark, named after Queen Beatrix.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Between Amsterdam and Amstelveen is the Amsterdamse Bos ("Amsterdam Forest"), the largest recreational area in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Annually, almost 4.5 million people visit the park, which has a size of 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres) and is approximately three times the size of Central Park.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The Amstelpark in the Zuid borough houses the Rieker windmill, which dates to 1636.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Other parks include the Sarphatipark in the De Pijp neighbourhood, the Oosterpark in the Oost borough and the Westerpark in the Westerpark neighbourhood.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city has three beaches: Nemo Beach, Citybeach "Het stenen hoofd" (Silodam), and Blijburg, all located in the Centrum borough.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The city has many open squares (*plein* in Dutch).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] The namesake of the city as the site of the original dam, Dam Square, is the main city square and has the Royal Palace and National Monument.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Museumplein hosts various museums, including the Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum, and Stedelijk Museum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p01] Other squares include Rembrandtplein, Muntplein, Nieuwmarkt, Leidseplein, Spui and Waterlooplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A substantial number of large corporations and banks' headquarters are located in the Amsterdam area, including: AkzoNobel, Heineken International, ING Group, ABN AMRO, TomTom, Delta Lloyd Group, Booking.com and Philips.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Although many small offices remain along the historic canals, centrally based companies have increasingly relocated outside Amsterdam's city centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The adjoining municipality of Amstelveen is the location of KPMG International's global headquarters.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Other non-Dutch companies have chosen to settle in communities surrounding Amsterdam since they allow freehold property ownership, whereas Amsterdam retains ground rent.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (AEX), now part of Euronext, is the world's oldest stock exchange and, due to Brexit, has overtaken LSE as the largest bourse in Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It is near Dam Square in the city centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Port of Amsterdam is the fourth-largest port in Europe, the 38th largest port in the world, and the second-largest port in the Netherlands by metric tons of cargo.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, the Port of Amsterdam had a cargo throughput of 97,4 million tons of cargo, which was mostly bulk cargo.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has the biggest cruise port in the Netherlands with more than 150 cruise ships every year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2019, the new lock in IJmuiden opened; since then, the port has been able to grow to 125 million tonnes in capacity.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Europe, receiving more than 5.34 million international visitors annually; this is excluding the 16 million day-trippers visiting the city every year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The number of visitors has been growing steadily over the past decade.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This can be attributed to an increasing number of European visitors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Two-thirds of the hotels are located in the city's centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Hotels with four or five stars contribute 42% of the total beds available and 41% of the overnight stays in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The room occupation rate was 85% in 2017, up from 78% in 2006.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The majority of tourists (74%) originate from Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The largest group of non-European visitors come from the United States, accounting for 14% of the total.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Certain years have a theme in Amsterdam to attract extra tourists.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] For example, the year 2006 was designated "Rembrandt 400", to celebrate the 400th birthday of Rembrandt van Rijn.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Some hotels offer special arrangements or activities during these years.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The average number of guests per year staying at the four campsites around the city ranges from 12,000 to 65,000.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2023, the city began running a campaign to dissuade British men between the ages of 18 and 35 from coming to the city as tourists.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The ad shows young men being handcuffed by police and is part of a new campaign to clean up the city's reputation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] On 25 May 2023, in a bid to crackdown on wild tourist behaviour, the city banned weed smoking in public areas in and around the red light district.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] De Wallen, also known as Walletjes or Rosse Buurt, is a designated area for legalised prostitution and is Amsterdam's largest and best-known red-light district.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This neighbourhood has become a famous attraction for tourists.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It consists of a network of canals, streets, and alleys containing several hundred small, one-room apartments rented by sex workers who offer their services from behind a window or glass door, typically illuminated with red lights.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In recent years, the city government has been closing and repurposing the famous red-light district windows to clean up the area and reduce the amount of party and sex tourism.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Shops in Amsterdam range from large high-end department stores such as De Bijenkorf founded in 1870 to small specialty shops.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's high-end shops are found in the streets P.C.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Hooftstraat and *Cornelis Schuytstraat*, which are located in the vicinity of the Vondelpark.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] One of Amsterdam's busiest high streets is the narrow, medieval Kalverstraat in the heart of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Other shopping areas include the *Negen Straatjes* and Haarlemmerdijk and Haarlemmerstraat.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] *Negen Straatjes* are nine narrow streets within the *Grachtengordel*, the concentric canal system of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Negen Straatjes differ from other shopping districts with the presence of a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Haarlemmerstraat and Haarlemmerdijk were voted the best shopping street in the Netherlands in 2011.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] These streets have as the *Negen Straatjes* a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The city also features a large number of open-air markets such as the Albert Cuyp Market, Westerstraat-markt, Ten Katemarkt, and Dappermarkt.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Some of these markets are held daily, like the Albert Cuypmarkt and the Dappermarkt.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Others, like the Westerstraatmarkt, are held every week.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Several fashion brands and designers are based in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Fashion designers include Iris van Herpen, Mart Visser, Viktor & Rolf, Marlies Dekkers and Frans Molenaar.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Fashion models like Yfke Sturm, Doutzen Kroes and Kim Noorda started their careers in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has its garment centre in the World Fashion Center.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Fashion photographers Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin were born in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] During the later part of the 16th century, Amsterdam's Rederijkerskamer (Chamber of rhetoric) organised contests between different Chambers in the reading of poetry and drama.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 1637, Schouwburg, the first theatre in Amsterdam was built, opening on 3 January 1638.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The first ballet performances in the Netherlands were given in Schouwburg in 1642 with the *Ballet of the Five Senses*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the 18th century, French theatre became popular.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] While Amsterdam was under the influence of German music in the 19th century there were few national opera productions; the Hollandse Opera of Amsterdam was built in 1888 for the specific purpose of promoting Dutch opera.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the 19th century, popular culture was centred on the Nes area in Amsterdam (mainly vaudeville and music-hall).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] An improved metronome was invented in 1812 by Dietrich Nikolaus Winkel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum (1885) and Stedelijk Museum (1895) were built and opened.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 1888, the Concertgebouworkest orchestra was established.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] With the 20th century came cinema, radio and television.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Though most studios are located in Hilversum and Aalsmeer, Amsterdam's influence on programming is very strong.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Many people who work in the television industry live in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Also, the headquarters of the Dutch SBS Broadcasting Group is located in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] There are also a number of cultural centers based in the city that produce public programs about the arts, sciences, politics and history, including de Balie and the John Adams Institute.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The most important museums of Amsterdam are located on the Museumplein (Museum Square), located at the southwestern side of the Rijksmuseum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It was created in the last quarter of the 19th century on the grounds of the former World's fair.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The northeastern part of the square is bordered by the large Rijksmuseum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In front of the Rijksmuseum on the square itself is a long, rectangular pond.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This is transformed into an ice rink in winter.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The northwestern part of the square is bordered by the Van Gogh Museum, House of Bols Cocktail & Genever Experience and Coster Diamonds.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The southwestern border of the Museum Square is the Van Baerlestraat, which is a major thoroughfare in this part of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Concertgebouw is located across this street from the square.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] To the southeast of the square are several large houses, one of which contains the American consulate.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A parking garage can be found underneath the square, as well as a supermarket.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Museumplein is covered almost entirely with a lawn, except for the northeastern part of the square which is covered with gravel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The current appearance of the square was realised in 1999 when the square was remodelled.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The square itself is the most prominent site in Amsterdam for festivals and outdoor concerts, especially in the summer.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Plans were made in 2008 to remodel the square again because many inhabitants of Amsterdam are not happy with its current appearance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum possesses the largest and most important collection of classical Dutch art.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Its collection consists of nearly one million objects.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The artist most associated with Amsterdam is Rembrandt, whose work, and the work of his pupils, is displayed in the Rijksmuseum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Rembrandt's masterpiece *The Night Watch* is one of the top pieces of art in the museum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It also houses paintings from artists like Bartholomeus van der Helst, Johannes Vermeer, Frans Hals, Ferdinand Bol, Albert Cuyp, Jacob van Ruisdael and Paulus Potter.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Aside from paintings, the collection consists of a large variety of decorative art.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This ranges from Delftware to giant doll-houses from the 17th century.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The architect of the gothic revival building was P.J.H.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The museum underwent a 10-year, 375 million euro renovation starting in 2003.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The full collection was reopened to the public on 13 April 2013.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum has remained the most visited museum in Amsterdam with 2.4 million visitors in 2024.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Van Gogh lived in Amsterdam for a short while and there is a museum dedicated to his work.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The museum is housed in one of the few modern buildings in this area of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The building was designed by Gerrit Rietveld.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This building is where the permanent collection is displayed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A new building was added to the museum in 1999.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This building, known as the performance wing, was designed by Japanese architect Kisho Kurokawa.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Its purpose is to house temporary exhibitions of the museum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Some of Van Gogh's most famous paintings, like *The Potato Eaters* and *Sunflowers*, are in the collection.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Van Gogh museum is the second most visited museum in Amsterdam, not far behind the Rijksmuseum in terms of the number of visits, being approximately 1.8 million in 2024.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Next to the Van Gogh Museum stands the Stedelijk Museum.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This is Amsterdam's most important museum of modern art.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The museum is as old as the square it borders and was opened in 1895.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The permanent collection consists of works of art from artists like Piet Mondrian, Karel Appel, and Kazimir Malevich.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] After renovations lasting several years, the museum opened in September 2012 with a new composite extension that has been called 'The Bathtub' due to its resemblance to one.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam contains many other museums throughout the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The modern-styled Nemo is dedicated to child-friendly science exhibitions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's musical culture includes a large collection of songs that treat the city nostalgically and lovingly.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The 1949 song "Aan de Amsterdamse grachten" ("On the canals of Amsterdam") was performed and recorded by many artists, including John Kraaijkamp Sr.; the best-known version is probably that by Wim Sonneveld (1962).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the 1950s Johnny Jordaan rose to fame with "Geef mij maar Amsterdam" ("I prefer Amsterdam"), which praises the city above all others (explicitly Paris); Jordaan sang especially about his own neighbourhood, the Jordaan ("Bij ons in de Jordaan").
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Colleagues and contemporaries of Johnny include Tante Leen and Manke Nelis.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Another notable Amsterdam song is "Amsterdam" by Jacques Brel (1964).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A 2011 poll by Amsterdam newspaper *Het Parool* that Trio Bier's "Oude Wolf" was voted "Amsterdams lijflied".
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Notable Amsterdam bands from the modern era include the Osdorp Posse and the Ex.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live (formerly known as the Heineken Music Hall) is a concert hall located near the Johan Cruyff Arena (known as the Amsterdam Arena until 2018).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Its main purpose is to serve as a podium for pop concerts for big audiences.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Many famous international artists have performed there.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Two other notable venues, Paradiso and the Melkweg are located near the Leidseplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Both focus on broad programming, ranging from indie rock to hip-hop, R&B, and other popular genres.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Other subcultural music venues are OCCII, OT301, De Nieuwe Anita, Winston Kingdom, and Zaal 100.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Jazz has a strong following in Amsterdam, with the Bimhuis being the premier venue.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, Ziggo Dome was opened, also near Amsterdam Arena, a state-of-the-art indoor music arena.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live is also host to many electronic dance music festivals, alongside many other venues.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Armin van Buuren and Tiesto, some of the world's leading Trance DJs hail from the Netherlands and frequently perform in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Each year in October, the city hosts the Amsterdam Dance Event (ADE) which is one of the leading electronic music conferences and one of the biggest club festivals for electronic music in the world, attracting over 350,000 visitors each year.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Another popular dance festival is 5daysoff, which takes place in the venues Paradiso and Melkweg.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the summertime, there are several big outdoor dance parties in or nearby Amsterdam, such as Awakenings, Dance Valley, Mystery Land, Loveland, A Day at the Park, Welcome to the Future, and Valtifest.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has a world-class symphony orchestra, the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Their home is the Concertgebouw, which is across the Van Baerlestraat from the Museum Square.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It is considered by critics to be a concert hall with some of the best acoustics in the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The building contains three halls, Grote Zaal, Kleine Zaal, and Spiegelzaal.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Some nine hundred concerts and other events per year take place in the Concertgebouw, for a public of over 700,000, making it one of the most-visited concert halls in the world.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The opera house of Amsterdam is located adjacent to the city hall.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, the two buildings combined are often called the Stopera, (a word originally coined by protesters against its very construction: *Stop the Opera[-house]*).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This huge modern complex, opened in 1986, lies in the former Jewish neighbourhood at *Waterlooplein* next to the river Amstel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The *Stopera* is the home base of Dutch National Opera, Dutch National Ballet and the Holland Symfonia.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ is a concert hall, which is located in the IJ near the central station.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Its concerts perform mostly modern classical music.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Located adjacent to it, is the *Bimhuis*, a concert hall for improvised and jazz music.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has three main theatre buildings.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Stadsschouwburg at the Leidseplein is the home base of Toneelgroep Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Most plays are performed in the Grote Zaal (Great Hall).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The normal program of events encompasses all sorts of theatrical forms.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2009, the new hall of the Stadsschouwburg Amsterdam, Toneelgroep Amsterdam, and Melkweg opened, and the renovation of the front end of the theatre was ready.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Dutch National Opera and Ballet (formerly known as *Het Muziektheater*), dating from 1986, is the principal opera house and home to Dutch National Opera and Dutch National Ballet.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Royal Theatre Carré was built as a permanent circus theatre in 1887 and is currently mainly used for musicals, cabaret performances, and pop concerts.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The recently re-opened DeLaMar Theater houses more commercial plays and musicals.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A new theatre has also moved into the Amsterdam scene in 2014, joining other established venues: Theater Amsterdam is located in the west part of Amsterdam, on the Danzigerkade.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It is housed in a modern building with a panoramic view over the harbour.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The theatre is the first-ever purpose-built venue to showcase a single play entitled ANNE, the play based on Anne Frank's life.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] On the east side of town, there is a small theatre in a converted bathhouse, the Badhuistheater.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The theatre often has English programming.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Netherlands has a tradition of cabaret or *kleinkunst*, which combines music, storytelling, commentary, theatre, and comedy.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Cabaret dates back to the 1930s and artists like Wim Kan, Wim Sonneveld, and Toon Hermans were pioneers of this form of art in the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In Amsterdam are the Kleinkunstacademie (English: Cabaret Academy) and Nederlied Kleinkunstkoor (English: Cabaret Choir).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Contemporary popular artists are Youp van 't Hek, Freek de Jonge, Herman Finkers, Hans Teeuwen, Theo Maassen, Herman van Veen, Najib Amhali, Raoul Heertje, Jörgen Raymann, Brigitte Kaandorp and Comedytrain.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The English-spoken comedy scene was established with the founding of Boom Chicago in 1993.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] They have their own theatre at Leidseplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is famous for its vibrant and diverse nightlife.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] They range from large and modern to small and cosy.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The typical *Bruine Kroeg* (brown *café*) breathes a more old-fashioned atmosphere with dimmed lights, candles, and somewhat older clientele.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] These brown cafés mostly offer a wide range of local and international artisanal beers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Most *cafés* have terraces in summertime.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A common sight on the Leidseplein during summer is a square full of terraces packed with people drinking beer or wine.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Many restaurants can be found in Amsterdam as well.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Since Amsterdam is a multicultural city, a lot of different ethnic restaurants can be found.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Restaurants range from being rather luxurious and expensive to being ordinary and affordable.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also possesses many discothèques.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The two main nightlife areas for tourists are the Leidseplein and the Rembrandtplein.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Paradiso, Melkweg and Sugar Factory are cultural centres, which turn into discothèques on some nights.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2008, there were 140 festivals and events in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] During the same year, Amsterdam was designated as the World Book Capital for one year by UNESCO.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] On Koningsdag—which is held each year on 27 April—hundreds of thousands of people travel to Amsterdam to celebrate with the city's residents.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The entire city becomes overcrowded with people buying products from the *free market*, or visiting one of the many music concerts.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The yearly Holland Festival attracts international artists and visitors from all over Europe.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Gay Pride is a yearly local LGBT parade of boats in Amsterdam's canals, held on the first Saturday in August.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The annual Uitmarkt is a three-day cultural event at the start of the cultural season in late August.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It offers previews of many different artists, such as musicians and poets, who perform on podia.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home of the *Eredivisie* football club AFC Ajax.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The stadium Johan Cruyff Arena is the home of Ajax.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It is located in the south-east of the city next to the new Amsterdam Bijlmer ArenA railway station.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Before moving to their current location in 1996, Ajax played their regular matches in the now demolished De Meer Stadion in the eastern part of the city or in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 1928, Amsterdam hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Olympic Stadium built for the occasion has been completely restored and is now used for cultural and sporting events, such as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 1920, Amsterdam assisted in hosting some of the sailing events for the Summer Olympics held in neighbouring Antwerp, Belgium by hosting events at Buiten IJ.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] They had also made a bid to host the 1952 and 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Helsinki and Barcelona.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The city holds the Dam to Dam Run, a 16 km (10 mi) race from Amsterdam to Zaandam, as well as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The ice hockey team Amstel Tijgers plays in the Jaap Eden ice rink.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The team competes in the Dutch Ice Hockey Premier League.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Speed skating championships have been held on the 400-meter lane of this ice rink.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam holds two American football franchises: the Amsterdam Crusaders and the Amsterdam Panthers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Pirates baseball team competes in the Dutch Major League.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] There are three field hockey teams: Amsterdam, Pinoké, and Hurley, who play their matches around the Wagener Stadium in the nearby city of Amstelveen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The basketball team MyGuide Amsterdam competes in the Dutch premier division and play their games in the Sporthallen Zuid.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] There is one rugby club in Amsterdam, which also hosts sports training classes such as RTC (Rugby Talenten Centrum or Rugby Talent Centre) and the National Rugby Stadium.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Since 1999, the city of Amsterdam honours the best sportsmen and women at the Amsterdam Sports Awards.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Boxer Raymond Joval and field hockey midfielder Carole Thate were the first to receive the awards, in 1999.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam hosted the World Gymnaestrada in 1991 and will do so again in 2023.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The city of Amsterdam is a municipality under the Dutch Municipalities Act.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive, and a mayor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Since 1981, the municipality of Amsterdam has gradually been divided into semi-autonomous boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts'.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Over time, a total of 15 boroughs were created.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] As with all Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive and a government appointed mayor (*burgemeester*).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The mayor is a member of the municipal executive board but also has individual responsibilities in maintaining public order.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] She replaces Eberhard van der Laan (Labour Party) who was the Mayor of Amsterdam from 2010 until his death in October 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] After the 2014 municipal council elections, a governing majority of D66, VVD and SP was formed – the first coalition without the Labour Party since World War II.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Next to the mayor, the municipal executive consists of eight *wethouders* ('alderpersons') appointed by the municipal council: four D66 alderpersons, two VVD alderpersons and two SP alderpersons.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] On 18 September 2017, it was announced by Eberhard van der Laan in an open letter to Amsterdam citizens that Kajsa Ollongren would take up his office as acting Mayor of Amsterdam with immediate effect due to ill health.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Ollongren was succeeded as acting Mayor by Eric van der Burg on 26 October 2017 and by Jozias van Aartsen on 4 December 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Unlike most other Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is subdivided into seven boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts', and the urban area of Weesp.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This system was gradually implemented in the 1980s to improve local governance.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The boroughs are responsible for many activities that had previously been run by the central city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the number of Amsterdam boroughs reached fifteen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Fourteen of those had their own district council (*deelraad*), elected by a popular vote.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The fifteenth, Westpoort, covers the harbour of Amsterdam and has very few residents.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, it was governed by the central municipal council.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Under the borough system, municipal decisions are made at the borough level, except for those affairs on the whole city such as major infrastructure projects, which are the jurisdiction of the central municipal authorities.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the borough system was restructured, in which many smaller boroughs merged into larger boroughs.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, under a reform of the Dutch Municipalities Act, the Amsterdam boroughs lost much of their autonomous status, as their district councils were abolished.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The municipal council of Amsterdam voted to maintain the borough system by replacing the district councils with smaller, but still directly elected district committees (*bestuurscommissies*).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Under a municipal ordinance, the new district committees were granted responsibilities through the delegation of regulatory and executive powers by the central municipal council.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] "Amsterdam" is usually understood to refer to the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Colloquially, some areas within the municipality, such as the town of Durgerdam, may not be considered part of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Department for Research and Statistics uses a fourth conurbation, namely the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* ('City Region of Amsterdam').
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The city region is similar to Greater Amsterdam but includes the municipalities of Zaanstad and Wormerland.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The smallest of these areas is the municipality of Amsterdam with a population of about 870,000 in 2021.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The larger conurbation had a population of over one million.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It includes the municipalities of Zaanstad, Wormerland, Oostzaan, Diemen, and Amstelveen only, as well as the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Greater Amsterdam includes 15 municipalities and had a population of 1,400,000 in 2021.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Though much larger in area, the population of this area is only slightly larger, because the definition excludes the relatively populous municipality of Zaanstad.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The largest area by population, the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam (Dutch: Metropoolregio Amsterdam), has a population of 2,33 million.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It includes for instance Zaanstad, Wormerland, Muiden, Abcoude, Haarlem, Almere and Lelystad but excludes Graft-De Rijp.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is part of the conglomerate metropolitan area Randstad, with a total population of 6,659,300 inhabitants.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Of these various metropolitan area configurations, only the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* (City Region of Amsterdam) has a formal governmental status.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Its responsibilities include regional spatial planning and metropolitan public transport concessions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Under the Dutch Constitution, Amsterdam is the capital of the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Since the 1983 constitutional revision, the constitution mentions "Amsterdam" and "capital" in chapter 2, article 32: The king's confirmation by oath and his coronation take place in "the capital Amsterdam" ("*de hoofdstad Amsterdam*").
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Previous versions of the constitution only mentioned "the city of Amsterdam" ("*de stad Amsterdam*").
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] For a royal investiture, therefore, the States General of the Netherlands (the Dutch Parliament) meets for a ceremonial joint session in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The ceremony traditionally takes place at the Nieuwe Kerk on Dam Square, immediately after the former monarch has signed the act of abdication at the nearby Royal Palace of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Normally, however, the Parliament sits in The Hague, the city which has historically been the seat of the Dutch government, the Dutch monarchy, and the Dutch supreme court.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Foreign embassies are also located in The Hague.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The coat of arms of Amsterdam is composed of several historical elements.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] First and centre are three St Andrew's crosses, aligned in a vertical band on the city's shield (although Amsterdam's patron saint was Saint Nicholas).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] These St Andrew's crosses can also be found on the city shields of neighbours Amstelveen and Ouder-Amstel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This part of the coat of arms is the basis of the flag of Amsterdam, flown by the city government, but also as civil ensign for ships registered in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Second is the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 1489, out of gratitude for services and loans, Maximilian I awarded Amsterdam the right to adorn its coat of arms with the king's crown.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Then, in 1508, this was replaced with Maximilian's imperial crown when he was crowned Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the early years of the 17th century, Maximilian's crown in Amsterdam's coat of arms was again replaced, this time with the crown of Emperor Rudolph II, a crown that became the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The lions date from the late 16th century, when the city and province became part of the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Last came the city's official motto: *Heldhaftig, Vastberaden, Barmhartig* ("Heroic, Determined, Merciful"), bestowed on the city in 1947 by Queen Wilhelmina, in recognition of the city's bravery during the Second World War.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Currently, there are sixteen tram routes and five metro routes.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] All are operated by the municipal public transport operator Gemeentelijk Vervoerbedrijf (GVB), which also runs the city bus network.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Four fare-free GVB ferries carry pedestrians and cyclists across the IJ lake to the borough of Amsterdam-Noord, and two fare-charging ferries run east and west along the harbour.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] There are also privately operated water taxis, a water bus, a boat-sharing operation, electric rental boats, and canal cruises, that transport people along Amsterdam's waterways.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Regional buses, and some suburban buses, are operated by Connexxion and EBS.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] International coach services are provided by FlixBus and BlaBlaCar Bus.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] To facilitate easier transport to the centre of Amsterdam, the city has various P+R Locations where people can park their car at an affordable price and transfer to one of the numerous public transport lines.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam was intended in 1932 to be the hub, a kind of Kilometre Zero, of the highway system of the Netherlands, with freeways numbered One to Eight planned to originate from the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The outbreak of the Second World War and shifting priorities led to the current situation, where only roads A1, A2, and A4 originate from Amsterdam according to the original plan.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The A3 to Rotterdam was cancelled in 1970 to conserve the Groene Hart.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Road A8, leading north to Zaandam and the A10 Ringroad were opened between 1968 and 1974.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Besides the A1, A2, A4 and A8, several freeways, such as the A7 and A6, carry traffic mainly bound for Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The A10 ringroad surrounding the city connects Amsterdam with the Dutch national network of freeways.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Interchanges on the A10 allow cars to enter the city by transferring to one of the 18 *city roads*, numbered S101 through to S118.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] These city roads are regional roads without grade separation, and sometimes without a central reservation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The S100 *Centrumring* is a smaller ring road circumnavigating the city's centre.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In the city centre, driving a car is discouraged.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Parking fees are expensive, and many streets are closed to cars or are one-way.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The local government sponsors carsharing and carpooling initiatives such as *Autodelen* and *Meerijden.nu*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The local government has also started removing parking spaces in the city in 2019, with the goal of removing 10,000 spaces (roughly 1,500 per year) by 2025.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is served by ten stations of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen (Dutch Railways).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Five are intercity stops: Sloterdijk, Zuid, Amstel, Bijlmer ArenA and Amsterdam Centraal.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The stations for local services are: Lelylaan, RAI, Holendrecht, Muiderpoort and Science Park.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Centraal is also an international railway station.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] From the station, there are regular services to destinations such as Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, France, Germany, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Among these trains are international trains of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen and Deutsche Bahn to Berlin, Eurostar services to Antwerp, Brussels, Paris and London and ICE services to Cologne and Frankfurt.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol is less than 20 minutes by train from Amsterdam Centraal station and is served by domestic and international intercity trains, such as Eurostar and EuroCity.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Schiphol is the largest airport in the Netherlands, the third-largest in Europe, and the 14th-largest in the world in terms of passengers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] It handles over 68 million passengers per year and is the home base of four airlines, KLM, Transavia, Martinair and Arkefly.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] As of 2014, Schiphol was the fifth busiest airport in the world measured by international passenger numbers.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This airport is 4 meters below sea level.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Although Schiphol is internationally known as Amsterdam Schiphol Airport it lies in the neighbouring municipality of Haarlemmermeer, southwest of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Rotterdam The Hague Airport, a smaller international airport, is also within an hour's drive of the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most bicycle-friendly large cities in the world and is a centre of bicycle culture with good facilities for cyclists such as bike paths and bike racks, and several guarded bike storage garages (*fietsenstalling*) which can be used.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] According to the most recent figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS), in 2015 the 442,693 households (850,000 residents) in Amsterdam together owned 847,000 bicycles – 1.91 bicycles per household.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Theft is widespread—in 2011, about 83,000 bicycles were stolen in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Bicycles are used by all socio-economic groups because of their convenience, Amsterdam's small size, the 400 km (249 mi) of bike paths, the flat terrain, and the inconvenience of driving an automobile.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has two universities: the University of Amsterdam (*Universiteit van Amsterdam*, UvA), and the *Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam* (VU).
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The University of Amsterdam is home to Room for Discussion, an independent interview platform that has welcomed a variety of prominent guests including Christine Lagarde, Mario Draghi, Charles Michel, Rob Bauer, and Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Other institutions for higher education include an art school – Gerrit Rietveld Academie, a university of applied sciences – the Hogeschool van Amsterdam, and the Amsterdamse Hogeschool voor de Kunsten.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's International Institute of Social History is one of the world's largest documentary and research institutions concerning social history, and especially the history of the labour movement.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's Hortus Botanicus, founded in the early 17th century, is one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world, with many old and rare specimens, among them the coffee plant that served as the parent for the entire coffee culture in Central and South America.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] There are over 200 primary schools in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Some of these primary schools base their teachings on particular pedagogic theories like the various Montessori schools.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The biggest Montessori high school in Amsterdam is the Montessori Lyceum Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Many schools, however, are based on religion.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] This used to be primarily Roman Catholicism and various Protestant denominations, but with the influx of Muslim immigrants, there has been a rise in the number of Islamic schools.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Jewish schools can be found in the southern suburbs of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is noted for having five independent grammar schools (Dutch: gymnasia), the Vossius Gymnasium, Barlaeus Gymnasium, St.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Ignatius Gymnasium, Het 4e Gymnasium and the Cygnus Gymnasium where a classical curriculum including Latin and classical Greek is taught.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Though believed until recently by many to be an anachronistic and elitist concept that would soon die out, the gymnasia have recently experienced a revival, leading to the formation of a fourth and fifth grammar school in which the three aforementioned schools participate.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Most secondary schools in Amsterdam offer a variety of different levels of education in the same school.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The city also has various colleges ranging from art and design to politics and economics which are mostly also available for students coming from other countries.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is a prominent centre for national and international media.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home to the second-largest Dutch commercial TV group SBS Broadcasting Group, consisting of TV stations SBS6, Net5, and Veronica.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] However, Amsterdam is not considered 'the media city of the Netherlands'.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The town of Hilversum, 30 km (19 mi) south-east of Amsterdam, has been crowned with this unofficial title.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is the principal centre for radio and television broadcasting in the Netherlands.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Radio Netherlands, heard worldwide via shortwave radio since the 1920s, is also based there.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is home to an extensive complex of audio and television studios belonging to the national broadcast production company NOS, as well as to the studios and offices of all the Dutch public broadcasting organisations and many commercial TV production companies.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, the music video for "Live My Life" by Far East Movement was filmed in various parts of Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Several movies have been filmed in Amsterdam, including the James Bond film *Diamonds Are Forever*, *Ocean's Twelve*, *Girl with a Pearl Earring*, *Kidnapping Mr.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Heineken*, *Layer Cake* and *The Hitman's Bodyguard*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is also featured in John Green's book *The Fault in Our Stars*, which was made into a film that also partly takes place in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] In 2003, the British drama series *Bad Girls* filmed scenes on location in Amsterdam.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] The scenes shows the male officers on a weekend trip in the red light district where they encounter escapee Shell Dockley and return her to the UK.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam appears as a multiplayer map in *Modern Warfare II* under the name Breenbergh Hotel.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also appears in *Black Ops Cold War* in an update, having players fight through the city.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] From the late 1960s onwards many buildings in Amsterdam have been squatted both for housing and for use as social centres.
[src:dnxhr-codec/amsterdam-p02] A number of these squats have legalised and become well known, such as OCCII, OT301, Paradiso and Vrankrijk.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Like VP9, but unlike H.264 (AVC) and H.265 (HEVC), AV1 has a royalty-free licensing model that does not hinder adoption in open-source projects.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AVIF is an image file format that uses AV1 compression algorithms.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Alliance's motivations for creating AV1 included the high cost and uncertainty involved with the patent licensing of HEVC (also known as H.265), the MPEG-designed codec expected to succeed AVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Additionally, the Alliance's seven founding members – Amazon, Cisco, Google, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Netflix – announced that the initial focus of the video format would be delivery of high-quality web video.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The official announcement of AV1 came with the press release on the formation of the Alliance for Open Media on 1 September 2015.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Only 42 days before, on 21 July 2015, HEVC Advance's initial licensing offer was announced to be an increase over the royalty fees of its predecessor, AVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In addition to the increased cost, the complexity of the licensing process increased with HEVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Unlike previous MPEG standards where the technology in the standard could be licensed from a single entity, MPEG LA, when the HEVC standard was finished, two patent pools had been formed with a third pool on the horizon.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In addition, various patent holders were refusing to license patents via either pool, increasing uncertainty about HEVC's licensing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] According to Microsoft's Ian LeGrow, an open-source, royalty-free technology was seen as the easiest way to eliminate this uncertainty around licensing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The negative effect of patent licensing on free and open-source software has also been cited as a reason for the creation of AV1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] For example, building an H.264 implementation into Firefox would prevent it from being distributed free of charge since licensing fees would have to be paid to MPEG-LA.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Free Software Foundation Europe has argued that FRAND patent licensing practices make the free software implementation of standards impossible due to various incompatibilities with free-software licenses.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Many of the components of the AV1 project were sourced from previous research efforts by Alliance members.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Individual contributors had started experimental technology platforms years before: Xiph's/Mozilla's Daala published code in 2010, Google's experimental VP9 evolution project VP10 was announced on 12 September 2014, and Cisco's Thor was published on 11 August 2015.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Building on the code base of VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques, several of which were developed in these experimental formats.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Many companies are part of Alliance for Open Media, including Samsung, Vimeo, Microsoft, Netflix, Mozilla, AMD, Nvidia, Intel, ARM, Google, Facebook, Cisco, Amazon, Hulu, VideoLAN, Adobe, and Apple.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Apple is an AOMedia governing member, although it joined after the formation.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The management of the AV1 streams has been officially included among the typological videos manageable by Coremedia.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The first version 0.1.0 of the AV1 reference codec was published on April 7, 2016.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Although a soft feature freeze came into effect at the end of October 2017, development continued on several significant features.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The bitstream format, was projected to be frozen in January 2018 but was delayed due to unresolved critical bugs as well as further changes to transformations, syntax, the prediction of motion vectors, and the completion of legal analysis.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Alliance announced the release of the AV1 bitstream specification on March 28, 2018, along with a reference, software-based encoder and decoder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On 25 June 2018, a validated version 1.0.0 of the specification was released.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On January 8, 2019, a validated *version 1.0.0 with Errata 1* of the specification was released.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Martin Smole from AOM member Bitmovin said that the computational efficiency was the greatest remaining challenge after the bitstream format freeze had been completed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] While working on the format, the encoder was not targeted for production use and speed optimizations were not prioritized.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Consequently, the early version of AV1 was orders of magnitude slower than existing HEVC encoders.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Much of the development effort was consequently shifted towards improving the reference encoder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In March 2019, it was reported that the speed of the reference encoder had improved greatly and was within the same order of magnitude as encoders for other common formats.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On January 21, 2021, the MIME type of AV1 was defined as `video/AV1`.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The usage of AV1 using this MIME type is restricted to Real-time Transport Protocol purposes only.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] For AOM's 10th birthday, the Alliance announced the successor to AV1 called AV2.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] It is designed to deliver better compression performance, enhanced support for AR, VR and split-screen usage and support for a wider visual quality range.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 aims to be a video format for the web that is both state-of-the-art and royalty free.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This concern has been raised regarding AV1, and previously VP8, VP9, Theora and IVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The problem is not unique to royalty-free formats, but it uniquely threatens their *status* as royalty-free.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] To fulfill the goal of being royalty free, the development process requires that no feature can be adopted before it has been confirmed independently by two separate parties to not infringe on patents of competing companies.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In cases where an alternative to a patent-protected technique is not available, owners of relevant patents have been invited to join the Alliance (even if they were already members of another patent pool).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] For example, Alliance members Apple, Cisco, Google, and Microsoft are also licensors in MPEG-LA's patent pool for H.264.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] As an additional protection for the royalty-free status of AV1, the Alliance has a legal defense fund to aid smaller Alliance members or AV1 licensees in the event they are sued for alleged patent infringement.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Under patent rules adopted from the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), technology contributors license their AV1-connected patents to anyone, anywhere, anytime based on reciprocity (i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigation).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] As a defensive condition, anyone engaging in patent litigation loses the right to the patents of *all* patent holders.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This treatment of intellectual property rights (IPR), and its absolute priority during development, is contrary to extant MPEG formats like AVC and HEVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] These were developed under an IPR uninvolvement policy by their standardization organisations, as stipulated in the ITU-T's definition of an open standard.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] However, MPEG's chairman has argued this practice has to change, which it is: EVC is also set to have a royalty-free subset, and will have switchable features in its bitstream to defend against future IPR threats.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The creation of royalty-free web standards has been a long-stated pursuit for the industry.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In 2007, the proposal for HTML video specified Theora as mandatory to implement.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The reason was that public content should be encoded in freely implementable formats, if only as a "baseline format", and that changing such a baseline format later would be hard because of network effects.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Alliance for Open Media is a continuation of Google's efforts with the WebM project, which renewed the royalty-free competition after Theora had been surpassed by AVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] For companies such as Mozilla that distribute free software, AVC can be difficult to support as a per-copy royalty is unsustainable given the lack of revenue stream to support these payments in free software (see FRAND § Excluding costless distribution).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Similarly, HEVC has not successfully convinced all licensors to allow an exception for freely distributed software (see HEVC § Provision for costless software).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The performance goals include "a step up from VP9 and HEVC" in efficiency for a low increase in complexity.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] NETVC's efficiency goal is 25% improvement over HEVC.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The primary complexity concern is for software decoding, since hardware support will take time to reach users.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] However, for WebRTC, live encoding performance is also relevant, which is Cisco's agenda: Cisco is a manufacturer of videoconferencing equipment, and their Thor contributions aim at "reasonable compression at only moderate complexity".
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] It is therefore planned to support the color space from ITU-R Recommendation BT.2020 and up to 12 bits of precision per color component.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 is primarily intended for lossy encoding, although lossless compression is supported as well.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 is a traditional block-based frequency transform format featuring new techniques.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Based on Google's VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques that mainly give encoders more coding options to enable better adaptation to different types of input.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Alliance published a reference implementation written in C and assembly language (`aomenc`, `aomdec`) as free software under the terms of the BSD 2-Clause License.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Development happens in public and is open for contributions, regardless of AOM membership.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] When the feature gained some support in the community, the experiment was enabled by default, and ultimately had its flag removed when all of the reviews were passed.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Experiment names were lowercased in the *configure* script and uppercased in conditional compilation flags.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] To better and more reliably support HDR and color spaces, corresponding metadata can now be integrated into the video bitstream instead of being signaled in the container.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Frame content is separated into adjacent same-sized blocks referred to as superblocks.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Similar to the concept of a macroblock, superblocks are square-shaped and can either be of size 128×128 or 64×64 pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Superblocks can be divided in smaller blocks according to different partitioning patterns.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The four-way split pattern is the only pattern whose partitions can be recursively subdivided.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This allows superblocks to be divided into partitions as small as 4×4 pixels.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] "T-shaped" partitioning patterns are introduced, a feature developed for VP10, as well as horizontal or vertical splits into four stripes of 4:1 and 1:4 aspect ratio.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The available partitioning patterns vary according to the block size, both 128×128 and 8×8 blocks can't use 4:1 and 1:4 splits.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Moreover, 8×8 blocks can't use T-shaped splits.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Two separate predictions can now be used on spatially different parts of a block using a smooth, oblique transition line (*wedge-partitioned prediction*).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This enables more accurate separation of objects without the traditional staircase lines along the boundaries of square blocks.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] More encoder parallelism is possible thanks to configurable prediction dependency between tile rows (`ext_tile`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 performs internal processing in higher precision (10 or 12 bits per sample), which leads to quality improvement by reducing rounding errors.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This allows the combination of either two inter predictions or an inter and an intra prediction to be used in the same block.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] A frame can reference 6 instead of 3 of the 8 available frame buffers for temporal (inter) prediction while providing more flexibility on bi-prediction (`ext_refs`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The *Warped Motion* (`warped_motion`) and *Global Motion* (`global_motion`) tools in AV1 aim to reduce redundant information in motion vectors by recognizing patterns arising from camera motion.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] They implement ideas that were attempted in preceding formats like e.g.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] MPEG-4 ASP, albeit with a novel approach that works in three dimensions.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] There can be a set of warping parameters for a whole frame offered in the bitstream, or blocks can use a set of implicit local parameters that get computed based on surrounding blocks.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Intra prediction consists of predicting the pixels of given blocks only using information available in the current frame.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Most often, intra predictions are built from the neighboring pixels above and to the left of the predicted block.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The DC predictor builds a prediction by averaging the pixels above and to the left of block.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Directional predictors extrapolate these neighboring pixels according to a specified angle.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In AV1, 8 main directional modes can be chosen.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] These modes start at an angle of 45 degrees and increase by a step size of 22.5 degrees up until 203 degrees.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Furthermore, for each directional mode, six offsets of 3 degrees can be signaled for bigger blocks, three above the main angle and three below it, resulting in a total of 56 angles (`ext_intra`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The "TrueMotion" predictor was replaced with a Paeth predictor which looks at the difference from the known pixel in the above-left corner to the pixel directly above and directly left of the new one and then chooses the one that lies in direction of the smaller gradient as predictor.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] A palette predictor is available for blocks with up to 8 dominant colors, such as some computer screen content.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Correlations between the luminosity and the color information can now be exploited with a predictor for chroma blocks that is based on samples from the luma plane (`cfl`), a technique borrowed from Daala.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In order to reduce visible boundaries along borders of inter-predicted blocks, a technique called overlapped block motion compensation (OBMC) can be used.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This involves extending a block's size so that it overlaps with neighboring blocks by 2 to 32 pixels, and blending the overlapping parts together.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] It can combine two one-dimensional transforms in order to use different transforms for the horizontal and the vertical dimension (`ext_tx`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 has new optimized quantization matrices (`aom_qm`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The eight sets of quantization parameters that can be selected and signaled for each frame now have individual parameters for the two chroma planes and can use spatial prediction.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On every new superblock, the quantization parameters can be adjusted by signaling an offset.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In-loop filtering combines Thor's constrained low-pass filter and Daala's directional deringing filter into the *Constrained Directional Enhancement Filter*, `cdef`.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This is an edge-directed conditional replacement filter that smooths blocks roughly along the direction of the dominant edge to eliminate ringing artifacts.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] There is also the *loop restoration filter* (`loop_restoration`) based on the Wiener filter and self-guided restoration filters to remove blur artifacts due to block processing.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Daala's entropy coder (`daala_ec`), a non-binary arithmetic coder, was selected for replacing VP9's binary entropy coder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The use of *non-binary* arithmetic coding helps evade patents but also adds bit-level parallelism to an otherwise serial process, reducing clock rate demands on hardware implementations.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] This is to say that the effectiveness of modern binary arithmetic coding like CABAC is being approached using a greater alphabet than binary, hence greater speed, as in Huffman code (but not as simple and fast as Huffman code).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 also gained the ability to adapt the symbol probabilities in the arithmetic coder per coded symbol instead of per frame (`ec_adapt`).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 has provisions for temporal and spatial scalability.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] A first comparison from the beginning of June 2016 found AV1 roughly on par with HEVC, as did one using code from late January 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In April 2017, using the 8 enabled experimental features at the time (of 77 total), Bitmovin was able to demonstrate favorable objective metrics, as well as visual results, compared to HEVC on the *Sintel* and *Tears of Steel* short films.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] A follow-up comparison by Jan Ozer of *Streaming Media Magazine* confirmed this, and concluded that "AV1 is at least as good as HEVC now".
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Ozer noted that his and Bitmovin's results contradicted a comparison by Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications from late 2016 that had found AV1 65.7% less efficient than HEVC, underperforming even H.264/AVC which they concluded as being 10.5% more efficient.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Ozer justified this discrepancy by having used encoding parameters endorsed by each encoder vendor, as well as having more features in the newer AV1 encoder.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Decoding performance was at about half the speed of VP9 according to internal measurements from 2017.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Tests from Netflix in 2017, based on measurements with PSNR and VMAF at 720p, showed that AV1 was about 25% more efficient than VP9 (libvpx).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Tests from Facebook conducted in 2018, based on PSNR, showed that the AV1 reference encoder was able to achieve 34%, 46.2% and 50.3% higher data compression than libvpx-vp9, x264 High profile, and x264 Main profile respectively.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Tests from Moscow State University in 2017 found that VP9 required 31% and HEVC 22% more bitrate than AV1 in order to achieve similar levels of quality.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The AV1 encoder was operating at speed "2500–3500 times lower than competitors" due to the lack of optimization (which was not available at that time).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] Tests from University of Waterloo in 2020 found that when using a mean opinion score (MOS) for 2160p (4K) video AV1 had the bitrate saving of 9.5% compared to HEVC and 16.4% compared to VP9.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] They also concluded that at the time of the study at 2160p the AV1 video encodes on average took 590× longer compared to encoding with AVC; while HEVC took on average 4.2× longer and VP9 took on average 5.2× longer than AVC respectively.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The best-in-test AV1 encoder, Visionular's Aurora1, in its "slower" preset, was as fast as *x265 veryslow* while saving 50% bitrate over *x264 veryslow*.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] CapFrameX tested the GPUs performance with AV1 decoding.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On 5 October 2022, Cloudflare announced that it has a beta player.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 defines three profiles for decoders which are Main, High, and Professional.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:0:0 (greyscale) and 4:2:0 (quarter) chroma sampling.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The High profile further adds support for 4:4:4 chroma sampling (no subsampling).
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The Professional profile extends capabilities to full support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2 (half) and 4:4:4 chroma sub-sampling with 8, 10 and 12 bit color depths.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 defines levels for decoders with maximum variables for levels ranging from 2.0 to 6.3.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] The levels that can be implemented depend on the hardware capability.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] A "Level 7" is mentioned but is not defined.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] AV1 video is usually accompanied with AAC or Opus audio in an ISO base media file format (MP4) container.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In October 2016, Netflix stated they expected to be an early adopter of AV1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On 5 February 2020, Netflix began using AV1 to stream select titles on Android, providing 20% improved compression efficiency over their VP9 streams.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] On 9 November 2021, Netflix announced it had begun streaming AV1 content to a number of TVs with AV1 decoders as well as the PlayStation 4 Pro.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In December 2025 they reported that 30% of their streams use AV1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In 2018, YouTube began deploying AV1, starting with its AV1 Beta Launch Playlist.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] According to the description, the videos are (to begin with) encoded at high bitrate to test decoding performance, and YouTube has "ambitious goals" for rolling out AV1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] YouTube for Android TV supports playback of videos encoded in AV1 on capable platforms as of version 2.10.13, released in early 2020.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In 2020, YouTube started serving videos at 8K resolution in AV1.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] In February 2019, Facebook followed its own positive test results, by saying it would gradually roll out the AV1 codec as soon as browser support emerges, starting with its most popular videos.
[src:dnxhr-codec/av1] MSVP (Meta Scalable Video Processor) was announced and the symposis was published in a popular scientific research website on 15 October 2022.
